<BODY>
<DIV1 TYPE="play">
<PB REF="3">
<HEAD>THE HIGHLAND REEL.</HEAD>
<DIV2 N="1" TYPE="act">
<HEAD>ACT I.</HEAD>
<STAGE>SCENE I. <HI>A &s;mall Court-yard before M'Gilpin's Hou&s;e, in<GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="pdcc" EXTENT="3 letters">&s;ed with a low Paling, and &s;mall Gate.</HI></STAGE>
<STAGE>Time&mdash;Morning Twilight.</STAGE>
<STAGE>(Charley appears at the Window.)</STAGE>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>CHARLEY.</SPEAKER>
<P>Day begins to peep&mdash;choak that Cock! he'll rou&s;e my old ma&s;ter; but if I can get his Daughter Moggy to run away with me, let Cocks crow, Dogs bark, and old Ma&s;ters grumble, <STAGE>(he &s;tretches out and taps at another Window.)</STAGE> Moggy! <STAGE>(&s;oftly.)</STAGE> Mi&s;s Moggy M'Gilpin!&mdash;ha, ha, ha!&mdash;I mu&s;t <HI>Mi&s;s</HI> Moggy her!</P>
</SP>
<STAGE>(Moggy appears at the window where Charley tapp'd.)</STAGE>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>MOG. </SPEAKER>
<STAGE>(Softly.)</STAGE>
<P>Well. Charley!</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>CHAR.</SPEAKER>
<P>Here: I've &s;tole the key of your room out of your father's pocket.</P>
<STAGE>(Reaches a key to fur on a &s;tick.)</STAGE>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>MOG.</SPEAKER>
<P>He, he, He! Oh, precious!</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>CHAR.</SPEAKER>
<P>I'll drop out of the window for &s;ear of making a noi&s;e on the &s;tairs; you've only to un|lock
<PB N="6" REF="4">your own door, &s;oltly trip down, I'll wait for you below.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>MOG.</SPEAKER>
<P>But how am I to get below? have you got the key of the <HI>&s;treet</HI> door?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>CHAR.</SPEAKER>
<P>Ecod! I had quite forgot <HI>that.</HI></P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>MOG.</SPEAKER>
<P>What a fool!&mdash;If I haven't a mind to go to bed again, and think no more about you&mdash;but &s;ince I did promi&s;e to go off with you, as we can't get out of the &s;treet door, I'll try to get from my win|dow; if you'll jump from yours, and &s;tand below ready to receive me.</P>
<STAGE>She retires.)</STAGE>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>CHAR. </SPEAKER>
<STAGE>(coming out of his window.)</STAGE>
<P>I'm not the fu&s;t clerk that's run away with his ma&s;ter's daughter, nor &s;hall I be the la&s;t&mdash;while clerks are poor, ma&s;ters rich, and daughters pretty.</P>
<STAGE>(Gets down.)</STAGE>
<STAGE>(Moggy re|appears at the window.)</STAGE>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>MOG.</SPEAKER>
<P>The duce a thing can I find to&mdash;Oh, Lord!&mdash;&s;top, I'll cut my bed cord, tie it to the leg of the table, and &s;lide down by it.</P>
<STAGE>(Retires.)</STAGE>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>CHAR.</SPEAKER>
<P>Slide down by her bed-cord! ha, ha, ha! my Moggy's a rare romping Hoyden&mdash;but &s;he's fun|ny and good-natur'd, a &s;weet temper, and a merry heart; &s;o if I never get a &s;hilling from the old one, I'll have her at a venture.</P>
<STAGE>(Moggy appears again at the window.)</STAGE>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>MOG. </SPEAKER>
<STAGE>(Throwing a cord.)</STAGE>
<P>There&mdash;I think that's fa&s;t&mdash;now I'll&mdash;Lud, I &s;hall cut my hands thro'&mdash;take you for not getting the key of the &s;treet door.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>CHAR.</SPEAKER>
<P>My dear! throw out fir&s;t what clothes you may want.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>MOG.</SPEAKER>
<P>Then you won't take me without clothes, ha, ha, ha!</P>
</SP>
<Q><TEXT LANG="eng">
<BODY>
<DIV1 TYPE="song">
<HEAD>DUETT</HEAD>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Moggy <HI>and</HI> Charley.</SPEAKER>
<L><HI>The lamb and the heifer are taking their re&s;t,</HI></L>
<L><HI>The lark and the &s;parrow lye &s;nug in their ne&s;t,</HI></L>
<L><HI>Pu&s;&s;ey do&s;es, and &s;o does my doggy,</HI></L>
<L><HI>All are &s;leeping but Charley and Moggy.</HI></L>
<L><HI>We wake to love before its day,</HI></L>
<L><HI>Come, my deare&s;t, we mu&s;t be tripping away.</HI></L>
<L><PB N="7" REF="5"><HI>No portion, dear Charley, if I marry thee,</HI></L>
<L><HI>My little old dad will give unto me;</HI></L>
<L><HI>Will love cool if you take me &s;o barely?</HI></L>
<L><HI>Moggy in her &s;inicket is welcome to Charley.</HI></L>
<L><HI>We wake to love, &amp;c.</HI></L>
</SP>
<STAGE>End of duett, Moggy retires.</STAGE>
</DIV1>
</BODY>
</TEXT></Q>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>CHAR.</SPEAKER>
<P>Ma&s;ter I think won't ri&s;e early&mdash;up late la&s;t night, rehear&s;ing his fine &s;peeches again&s;t he's a Parliament-man in London&mdash;Ha! ha! ha! tho' only now Laird Donald's &s;teward, and collector of taxes here in one of the remote we&s;tern i&s;lands of Scotland! ha! ha! he bani&s;hed a &s;imple old woman for a witch, 'cau&s;e &s;he foretold his daughter &s;hould be run away with&mdash;ha! ha! ha! &s;o I'll prove the truth of her prediction.&mdash;Od&s;o!&mdash;here's the little gate too locked!&mdash;now could Moggy&mdash;&s;tay&mdash;here's the hor&s;e block, and I'll make free with Dick the carpenter's bench, for her to &s;tep on the out&s;ide.&mdash;</P>
<STAGE>(Springs over the paling.)</STAGE>
</SP>
<STAGE>Exit.</STAGE>
<STAGE><HI>Enter</HI> M'Gilpin <HI>from the hou&s;e.</HI></STAGE>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>M'GIL.</SPEAKER>
<P>I will believe in witcherafts, in wizards, and warlocks!&mdash;tho' I did pack Goody Commings out of the i&s;land, yet I'm certain her elves have been about my hou&s;e t'night&mdash;no noi&s;e in Jenny's room, nor in my daughter Moggy's, nor in Charley's, nor in Benin's&mdash;yet noi&s;es I mo&s;t a&s;&s;uredly heard. <STAGE><HI>(Moggy from her window lowers a box on M'Gilpin's head.)</HI>&mdash;</STAGE> Eh!&mdash;</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>MOG.</SPEAKER>
<P>Have you got it?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>M'GIL.</SPEAKER>
<P>Yes, <STAGE>(feels his head, as if hurt.)</STAGE> I have got it!&mdash;what!&mdash;my daughter! oh! oh!</P>
<STAGE>(A&s;ide.)</STAGE>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>MOG.</SPEAKER>
<P>I thought I heard my father&mdash;</P>
<STAGE>(&s;oftly.)</STAGE>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>M'GIL.</SPEAKER>
<P>So did I!</P>
<STAGE>(in an under tone.)</STAGE>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>MOG.</SPEAKER>
<P>Do you think he's get up?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>M'GIL.</SPEAKER>
<P>No.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>MOG.</SPEAKER>
<P>Now you'll catch me!</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>M'GIL.</SPEAKER>
<P>Yes, I'll catch you, you jade.</P>
<STAGE>(a&s;ide.)</STAGE>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>MOG.</SPEAKER>
<P>Now for it.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<PB N="8" REF="6">
<SPEAKER>M'GIL.</SPEAKER>
<P>The devil!&mdash;&s;he wont jump out of the window.</P>
<STAGE>(a&s;ide.)</STAGE>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>MOG. <HI>Now.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>my fine fellow&mdash;here goes&mdash;</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>M'GIL.</SPEAKER>
<P>Oh, Lord! my child will break her bones. <STAGE>(A&s;ide.)</STAGE>&mdash;&s;top&mdash;can't you come out of the &s;treet door? It's open.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>MOG.</SPEAKER>
<P>P&s;haw!&mdash;why didn't you tell me &s;o before? &mdash;Upon my word, I don't like &s;uch jokes&mdash;</P>
<STAGE>(retire and goes down.)</STAGE>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>M'GIL.</SPEAKER>
<P>Nor I, upon my &s;oul. <STAGE>(A&s;ide.)</STAGE>&mdash;If I could carry on her mi&s;take, I may find out who her &s;educer is&mdash;I think it is &s;carce light enough for her to know me now.</P>
<STAGE>(Retires on one &s;ide.)</STAGE>
</SP>
<STAGE><HI>Re-enter</HI> Charley <HI>with a bench, which he places near the rails.</HI></STAGE>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>CHAR.</SPEAKER>
<P>There's a wooden &s;tepping-&s;tone for you my dear&mdash;Eh! <STAGE>(looking towards the door,)</STAGE> the door open! we mu&s;t have rou&s;ed the old man; he mu&s;t &s;ee me <STAGE>(retiring.)</STAGE>&mdash;Who comes here?&mdash;Shelty, the piper&mdash;</P>
</SP>
<STAGE><HI>Enter</HI> Shelty, <HI>&s;inging.</HI></STAGE>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>SHEL.</SPEAKER>
<P>If Sandy and Jenny are to be married to|day, it's time to rou&s;e the boys and girls.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>M'GIL.</SPEAKER>
<P>I think I know that voice&mdash;Oh, this is her fine fellow, I &s;uppo&s;e.</P>
<STAGE>(a&s;ide.)</STAGE>
<STAGE>(Enter Moggy from the hou&s;e.)</STAGE>
<STAGE>(Charley &s;teals into the hou&s;e.)</STAGE>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>MOG.</SPEAKER>
<P>Come now, I'm for you, my Dilding.</P>
<STAGE>(Takes M'Gilpin under the arm)</STAGE>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>M'GIL.</SPEAKER>
<P>And I'm for you my Dodling.</P>
<STAGE>In his own voice, laying hold of her.</STAGE>
</SP>
<STAGE>MOG. <HI>(Skreams.)</HI></STAGE>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>M'GIL.</SPEAKER>
<P>And pray, my dear, where were you go|ing &s;o early? Eh!</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>MOG.</SPEAKER>
<P>Going, Sir,&mdash;I&mdash;I&mdash;was going&mdash;</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>M'GIL.</SPEAKER>
<P>I know you were going, Sir,&mdash;but where, Sir?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>MOG.</SPEAKER>
<P>To&mdash;to&mdash;church, Sir.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<PB N="9" REF="7">
<SPEAKER>M'GIL.</SPEAKER>
<P>Jump out of the window to go to church!</P>
</SP>
<STAGE><HI>Enter</HI> Charley <HI>from the hou&s;e, half undre&s;s'd, pretending to be &s;carce awake.</HI></STAGE>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>CHAR.</SPEAKER>
<P>Aw, aw!&mdash;What's the matter here?&mdash;Aw&mdash;aw&mdash;</P>
<STAGE>(Yawning.)</STAGE>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>M'GIL.</SPEAKER>
<P>Where have you been, &s;irrah?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>CHAR.</SPEAKER>
<P>Sir,&mdash;I&mdash;I&mdash;was&mdash;aw&mdash;aw&mdash;fa&s;t &s;leep.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>M'GIL.</SPEAKER>
<P>You &s;tupid&mdash;Where's Jenny?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>CHAR.</SPEAKER>
<P>Sir,&mdash;&s;he's&mdash;aw&mdash;aw&mdash;fa&s;t a&s;leep.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>M'GIL.</SPEAKER>
<P>You lazy lubber!&mdash;Snoring in bed, and robbers and ravi&s;hers running away with my daugh|ter&mdash; <STAGE>(to Shelty.)</STAGE> Sirrah, what do you want with my daughter?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>SHEL.</SPEAKER>
<P>I&mdash;</P>
<STAGE>(looking &s;imply.)</STAGE>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>CHAR.</SPEAKER>
<P>Eh&mdash;Shelty&mdash;Moggy&mdash;ho, ho&mdash; <STAGE><HI>(looking at them)</HI>&mdash;</STAGE> Well, hang me if I didn't long &s;u&s;pect this,&mdash; <STAGE>(apart to Mog.)</STAGE> turn it upon him, and we are &s;afe.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>MOG.</SPEAKER>
<P>Go, my dear Shelty.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>SHEL.</SPEAKER>
<P>Eh!</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>MOG.</SPEAKER>
<P>Don't &s;educe my innocence any more.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>SHEL.</SPEAKER>
<P>I &s;educe!</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>MOG.</SPEAKER>
<P>Your wanting me to jump out of the win|dow to you.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>SHEL.</SPEAKER>
<P>I&mdash;jump!</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>M'GIL.</SPEAKER>
<P>To make a girl perhaps break her bones!</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>MOG.</SPEAKER>
<P>Ay&mdash;my poor little bones!&mdash;cruel lad!</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>CHAR.</SPEAKER>
<P>Oh, fie, Shelty&mdash;Ble&s;s me! how came the hor&s;e-block, and the carpenter's bench here? <STAGE><HI>(affect|ing &s;urprize.)</HI>&mdash;</STAGE> I dare &s;ay, to help Mi&s;s over.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>M'GIL.</SPEAKER>
<P>It was.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>MOG.</SPEAKER>
<P>My kind Shelty placed them.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>SHEL,</SPEAKER>
<P>Why, is the devil in you all?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>M'GIL.</SPEAKER>
<P>Don't name the devil, you profligate! You're as wicked as the witch your grandmother, and the &s;muggling thief your father?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>SHEL.</SPEAKER>
<P>My granny was an innocent old woman, and &s;o is my daddy. <STAGE>(Enter Croudy)</STAGE> Here father.
<PB N="10" REF="8">I only came to &s;ee about Sandy and Jenny's wedding, 'cau&s;e I hop'd to &s;ell a drop of liquor, and be em|ploy'd to play the pipes, and here, he &s;ays, I come to jump out of his window.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>M'GIL.</SPEAKER>
<P>A piper! a tap&s;ter!&mdash;marry into the an|cient family of the M'Gilpins&mdash;one of the olde&s;t hou&s;es in all Scotland!</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>SHEL.</SPEAKER>
<P>I don't want to come near your old hou&s;e.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>M'GIL.</SPEAKER>
<P>You are a young&mdash;and your father there, is an old rogue&mdash;</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>CROU.</SPEAKER>
<P>What?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>M'GIL.</SPEAKER>
<P><HI>You</HI> come to &s;teal my daughter, and <HI>he</HI> to rob the King.&mdash;I &s;ee he has been out, &s;mug|gling all night;&mdash;but as I am a collector of his Maje&s;ty's cu&s;toms, and my Laird Donald's rents, I'll&mdash;</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>CROU.</SPEAKER>
<P>You're a dog in office&mdash;I owe the King his duty; the Laird a quarter's rent, and you a beat|ing&mdash;all which I will pay, &s;o help me, bonnet, pur&s;e, and cudgel!&mdash;</P>
</SP>
<STAGE>Exit.</STAGE>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>M'GIL.</SPEAKER>
<P>He threatens my life?&mdash;A con&s;piracy to run away with my daughter!&mdash;Charley, I commit her to your care.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>MOG.</SPEAKER>
<P>Oh, cruel father!</P>
<STAGE>(Charley takes hold of her.)</STAGE>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>M'GIL.</SPEAKER>
<P>Take her, Charley.&mdash;You marry, you jade! you &s;han't be even pre&s;ent at a wedding&mdash;I'll have Sandy and Jenny's celebrated to-day, and, oh, not a peep at it&mdash;up to your malepardis &mdash;go&mdash;!</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>CHAR.</SPEAKER>
<P>Come, Mi&s;s; I'll take care you don't mar|ry any body&mdash;but my&s;elf&mdash;</P>
<STAGE>(apart.)</STAGE>
<STAGE>Takes Moggy into the hou&s;e.)</STAGE>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>M'GIL.</SPEAKER>
<P>That's right, Charley&mdash;</P>
</SP>
<STAGE>Exit into the hou&s;e.</STAGE>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>SHEL.</SPEAKER>
<P>Well, if ever I &s;aw &s;uch capers! the older he grows, the wickeder he is&mdash;ay, that's be|cau&s;e every day he gets nearer&mdash; <STAGE>(points downward)</STAGE> &mdash;Yes, he will&mdash;Eh&mdash; <STAGE><HI>(looking out.)</HI>&mdash;</STAGE> As well as I
<PB N="11" REF="9">can di&s;tingui&s;h, yonder &s;eems a boat put off from that &s;hip that cou'dn't get in la&s;t night.&mdash;I may pick up cu&s;tomers among the pa&s;&s;engers, they can't come to a nearer hou&s;e than mine.&mdash;People may at their friends be better entertain'd, but the &s;ure&s;t wel|come is at an inn.&mdash;Every body &s;ays&mdash;ha! ha! ha! that Shelty's a queer fellow; I believe I am &mdash;but I don't know how&mdash;how I get on&mdash;I do&mdash;I will.</P>
</SP>
<Q><TEXT LANG="eng">
<BODY>
<DIV1 TYPE="song">
<HEAD>AIR.</HEAD>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Shelty.</SPEAKER>
<LG>
<L><HI>When I've money I am merry,</HI></L>
<L><HI>When I've none I'm very &s;ad;</HI></L>
<L><HI>When I'm &s;ober I am civil,</HI></L>
<L><HI>When I'm drunk I'm roaring mad.</HI></L>
<L><HI>With my titol teedle tum,</HI></L>
<L><HI>Likewi&s;e fol lol feedle fum,</HI></L>
<L><HI>Not forgetting diderum hi,</HI></L>
<L><HI>And al&s;o teedle, tweedle dum.</HI></L>
</LG>
<LG>
<L><HI>When di&s;puting with a puppy</HI></L>
<L><HI>I convince him with a rap;</HI></L>
<L><HI>When I'm romping with a girl,</HI></L>
<L><HI>By accident I tear her cap.</HI></L>
<L><HI>Gadzooks, I'll never marry,</HI></L>
<L><HI>I'm a lad that's bold and free;</HI></L>
<L><HI>Yet I love a pretty girl,</HI></L>
<L><HI>A pretty girl is fond of me.</HI></L>
<L><HI>With my, &amp;c.</HI></L>
</LG>
<LG>
<L><HI>There's a maiden in a corner,</HI></L>
<L><HI>Round and &s;ound, and plump and fat;</HI></L>
<L><HI>She and I drank tea together,</HI></L>
<L><HI>But no matter, Sir, for that.</HI></L>
<L><HI>If this maiden be wi' bairn,</HI></L>
<L><HI>As I do &s;uppo&s;e &s;he'll be;</HI></L>
<L><HI>Like good pappy I mu&s;t learn</HI></L>
<L><HI>To dandle Jacky on my knee.</HI></L>
<L><HI>With my titol teedle dum. &amp;c.</HI></L>
</LG>
</SP>
</DIV1>
</BODY>
</TEXT></Q>
<STAGE>Exit.</STAGE>
<STAGE>(During the whole of this &s;cene, the morning light enerea&s;es gradually.)</STAGE>
<STAGE><PB N="12" REF="10"><HI>Enter</HI> M'Gilpin <HI>and</HI> Charley.</STAGE>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>M'GIL</SPEAKER>
<P>Oh, my daughter is a mo&s;t degenorate girl!&mdash;Well, you've lock'd her up?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>CHAR.</SPEAKER>
<P>Yes, Sir&mdash;</P>
<STAGE>(Shews a key.)</STAGE>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>M'GIL.</SPEAKER>
<P>Eh, ay&mdash;boy, li&s;ten&mdash;I'm certain from that old &s;muggling knave Croudy's being towards the &s;ea &s;ide &s;o early, that he's about landing brandy and tobacco; &s;o if I can but make a &s;eizure, it may be worth ten times the cargo of tea I &s;eiz'd on him la&s;t week; &s;o my good lad, you'll be on the look-out; ay, and on the look-<HI>in</HI> too; to watch imports, and prevent exports.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>CHAR.</SPEAKER>
<P>I warrant, Sir, I'll keep one eye on the &s;ea, and 'tother on Mi&s;s Moggy's room door.&mdash;Oh, Lord, Sir, yonder's Sandy come home.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>M'GIL.</SPEAKER>
<P>Ha! ha! ha! Aye, the fool went to Mule to buy wedding clothes for him&s;elf and Jenny&mdash;I gave her an education, and I think that was doing very hand&s;ome by her&mdash;So I make a great compliment in giving her to Sandy, tho'&mdash;Ha! ha! ha! I'm very glad&mdash;he rids me of a burden&mdash;that's prudence, Char|ley&mdash;Ha! ha! ha!</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>CHAR.</SPEAKER>
<P>'Tis, Sir, ha, ha, ha!</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>M'GIL.</SPEAKER>
<P>You know I taught you &s;ome of my tricks, ha, ha, ha!</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>CHAR.</SPEAKER>
<P>Yes, Sir, and you'll find me an apt &s;cholar.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>M'GIL.</SPEAKER>
<P>In return, Charley, all I a&s;k is your care of my daughter.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>CHAR.</SPEAKER>
<P>I'll take care of her, Sir.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>M'GIL.</SPEAKER>
<P>Keep her from Shelty.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>CHAR.</SPEAKER>
<P>I'll keep her from Shelty, don't fear, Sir.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>M'GIL.</SPEAKER>
<P>My good boy, how much I'm obliged to you. How &s;hall I reward you?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>CHAR.</SPEAKER>
<P>I &s;hall want ca&s;h for our frolic. A choice opportunity to coax him out of a little.</P>
<STAGE>A&s;ide.</STAGE>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>M'GIL.</SPEAKER>
<P>Only let me know what I &s;hou'd do for you.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>CHAR.</SPEAKER>
<P>Why, Sir, la&s;t Chri&s;tmas you promis'd me a Chri&s;tmas-box&mdash;now didn't you, Sir?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<PB N="13" REF="11">
<SPEAKER>M'GIL.</SPEAKER>
<P>I did &s;o, my faithful Charley; keep <GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="pdcc" EXTENT="1 letter">ut a &s;trict watch upon Moggy, and&mdash;may be you <GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="pdcc" EXTENT="1 letter">ave thoughts of &s;ome little blo&s;&s;om your&s;elf; only <GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="pdcc" EXTENT="1 word"> me know the girl that can make you happy, and <GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="pdcc" EXTENT="1 word"> &s;hall have her, by my authority.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>CHAR.</SPEAKER>
<P>Ah! Sir, there is a girl.&mdash;</P>
</SP>
<Q><TEXT LANG="eng">
<BODY>
<DIV1 TYPE="song">
<HEAD>DUET. M'Gilpin <HI>and</HI> Charley.</HEAD>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>M'Gil.</SPEAKER>
<L><HI>Thy &s;ecrets to thy kind ma&s;ter tell,</HI></L>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Cha.</SPEAKER>
<L><HI>I love a maid</HI>&mdash;</L>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>M'Gil.</SPEAKER>
<L><HI>. . . . . Is &s;he full of play;</HI></L>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Cha.</SPEAKER>
<L><HI>No kid more game&s;ome&mdash;</HI></L>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>M'Gil.</SPEAKER>
<L><HI>. . . . . . . Where does &s;he dwell?</HI></L>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Char.</SPEAKER>
<L><HI>Twang lango tillo, lang twang dillo day.</HI></L>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>M'Gil.</SPEAKER>
<L><HI>If you're in love, boy, you're not to blame;</HI></L>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Char.</SPEAKER>
<L><HI>As <GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="pdcc" EXTENT="2 letters">ch, kind Sir, I've heard you &s;ay,</HI></L>
<L><HI>I love my charming</HI></L>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>M'Gil.</SPEAKER>
<L><HI>. . . . . Ah&mdash;what's her name?</HI></L>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Char.</SPEAKER>
<L><HI>Twang lango tillo, lang twango dillo day.</HI></L>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Char.</SPEAKER>
<L><HI>My Chri&s;tmas-box,</HI></L>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>M'Gil.</SPEAKER>
<L><HI>. . . . . .  Oh, I under&s;tand,</HI></L>
<L><HI>Thy faithful &s;ervices I'll repay;</HI></L>
<L><HI>Here's five bright &s;hillings,</HI></L>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Char.</SPEAKER>
<L><HI>. . . . . . . . And here's my hand.</HI></L>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>M'Gil.</SPEAKER>
<L><HI>Twang lango tillo, &amp;c.</HI></L>
</SP>
</DIV1>
</BODY>
</TEXT></Q>
<STAGE>[<HI>As Charley holds out his hand in expectation, M'Gil|<GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="pdcc" EXTENT="3 letters"> fir&s;t making a &s;hew as to give him the money, turns and puts it up again&mdash;&s;inging the Burden, in imitation of Charley's manner in the preceding &s;tanzas.</HI>]</STAGE>
<STAGE>Exit Char. and M'Gilpin.</STAGE>
<STAGE>Scene&mdash;An open Country, with a view of the Sea&mdash;Sun ri&s;ing.</STAGE>
<STAGE><HI>Enter</HI> M'Gilpin.</STAGE>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>M'GIL.</SPEAKER>
<P>No, no, my kind Charley&mdash;I've a great regard for you; but touch my pocket and our friend&s;hip ends; &s;ince they've rai&s;ed me out of my bed, I'll walk down to the beach, and like another Demo&s;thenes, practi&s;e one of my declamations; a <GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="pdcc" EXTENT="1 letter">ine high wind for it.&mdash;This prever&s;e girl! Oh, yes,
<PB N="14" REF="12">with her beauty and my talents, I mu&s;t rai&s;e a for tune by going to London. <STAGE>(Sandy &s;ings without.)</STAGE> Ah, Sandy! this poor orphan, Jenny&mdash;he &s;hall have her&mdash;ha, ha, ha! here comes the &s;imple Sawny, that prefers love to money.</P>
</SP>
<STAGE><HI>Enter</HI> Sandy.</STAGE>
<P>Ha, Sandy! welcome home, my boy!</P>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>SAN. </SPEAKER>
<STAGE>(Joyful)</STAGE>
<P>Here, Sir, I've got all out wedding geer in the newe&s;t Edinbro' ta&s;te.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>M'GIL.</SPEAKER>
<P>But when comes the Par&s;on?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>SAN.</SPEAKER>
<P>He's gone over to Raa&s;ey! &s;o I de&s;ired Jamy M'Kenzie to &s;end us their new Curate.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>M'GIL.</SPEAKER>
<P>Stop, Sandy, I've one word to &s;ay to you.&mdash;Hem!</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>SAN.</SPEAKER>
<P>Delay'd now by his non&s;en&s;ical oratorical &s;peeches, and my &s;oul on the wing to love and Jenny!</P>
<STAGE>(a&s;ide.)</STAGE>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>M'GIL.</SPEAKER>
<P>Sandy, you have, by &s;kill in agricul|ture, which you acquir'd, as you &s;ay, in an excur|&s;ion to England, not only improv'd your own farm, but diffus'd &s;uch a &s;pirit of indu&s;try, that my mai&s;ter, Laird Donald, if he &s;hould deign to vi&s;it us, will find his I&s;le of Col as finely cultivated, as any patch of land in all Scotland; therefore to re|ward you, your Jenny you &s;hall wed this day.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>SAN.</SPEAKER>
<P>And yonder &s;he comes, bright as the morn, that gives the flowers their beauty; welcome as the gale that wafts its &s;weetne&s;s.</P>
</SP>
<Q><TEXT LANG="eng">
<BODY>
<DIV1 TYPE="song">
<HEAD>AIR.</HEAD>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Sandy.</SPEAKER>
<LG>
<L><HI>Oh, had I Allan Ram&s;ey's art</HI></L>
<L><HI>To &s;ing my pa&s;&s;ion tender,</HI></L>
<L><HI>In every ver&s;e &s;hall read my heart,</HI></L>
<L><HI>Such &s;oothing &s;trains I'll &s;end her;</HI></L>
<L><HI>Nor his, nor gentle Rizzio's aid</HI></L>
<L><HI>To &s;hew, is all a folly,</HI></L>
<L><HI>How much I love the charming maid,</HI></L>
<L><HI>Sweet Jane of Gri&s;&s;ipoly.</HI></L>
</LG>
<LG>
<PB N="15" REF="13">
<L><HI>She makes me know what all de&s;ire,</HI></L>
<L><HI>So rogui&s;h are her glances,</HI></L>
<L><HI>Her mode&s;t air then checks my fire,</HI></L>
<L><HI>And &s;tops my bold advances.</HI></L>
<L><HI>Meek as the lamb, on yonder lawn,</HI></L>
<L><HI>Yet by her conquered wholly;</HI></L>
<L><HI>For &s;prightly as the bounding fawn,</HI></L>
<L><HI>Sweet Jane of Gri&s;&s;ipoly.</HI></L>
</LG>
<LG>
<L><HI>My &s;en&s;es &s;he's bewildered quite,</HI></L>
<L><HI>I &s;eem an amorous ninny;</HI></L>
<L><HI>A letter to a friend I write,</HI></L>
<L><HI>For Sandy I &s;ign Jenny.</HI></L>
<L><HI>La&s;t Sunday when from Church I came,</HI></L>
<L><HI>With looks demure and holy,</HI></L>
<L><HI>I cry'd, when a&s;k'd the text to name,</HI></L>
<L><HI>'Twas Jane of Gri&s;&s;ipoly.</HI></L>
</LG>
<LG>
<L><HI>My Jenny is no fortune great,</HI></L>
<L><HI>And I am poor and lowly,</HI></L>
<L><HI>A &s;traw for pow'r and grand e&s;tate,</HI></L>
<L><HI>Her per&s;on I love &s;olely.</HI></L>
<L><HI>From every &s;ordid &s;elfi&s;h view,</HI></L>
<L><HI>So free my heart is wholly,</HI></L>
<L><HI>And &s;he is <GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="pdcc" EXTENT="1 word">, and I am true,</HI></L>
<L><HI>Sweet Jane of Gri&s;&s;ipoly.</HI></L>
</LG>
</SP>
</DIV1>
</BODY>
</TEXT></Q>
<STAGE><HI>Enter</HI> Jenny.</STAGE>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>JEN.</SPEAKER>
<P>Welcome home my Sandy!</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>SAN. </SPEAKER>
<STAGE>(Embrace.)</STAGE>
<P>My love!</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>M'GIL.</SPEAKER>
<P>Ah, hah!&mdash;Egad my Highland Lad and Lowland La&s;&s;ie, you'll make a neat couple, ha, ha, ha!</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>JEN.</SPEAKER>
<P>Dear, Sir, take the only return in my power, my thanks, my gratitude, for your unme|rited goodne&s;s.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>M'GIL.</SPEAKER>
<P>Ah, Jenny, was I the man that boa&s;ted of his goodne&s;s. I'd remind you, that I gave you an A&s;ylum, when you was but a &s;qualling bairn&mdash;tho' I did'nt, nor I &s;uppo&s;e I ever &s;hall, know what family you are of; your mother coming here to Col to lye|in, privately, and dying in my hou&s;e&mdash;yet my a&s;to|ni&s;hing benevolence, Oh!&mdash;</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<PB N="16" REF="14">
<SPEAKER>SAN.</SPEAKER>
<P>Your benevolence would be a&s;toni<GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="pdcc" EXTENT="5 letters"> indeed!</P>
<STAGE>(a&s;ide.)</STAGE>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>M'GIL.</SPEAKER>
<P>I &s;ay, my amazing charity, did&mdash;</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>SAN.</SPEAKER>
<P>Well, Sir, we have heard that <GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="pdcc" EXTENT="1 span"> often&mdash;</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>M'GIL.</SPEAKER>
<P>To be &s;ure; wou'd you have me put a candle under a bu&s;hel? Speak, Jenny, didn't I <GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="pdcc" EXTENT="1 word"> you up equal to my own daughter, Mi&s;s <GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="pdcc" EXTENT="1 word"> M'Gilpin? &s;ent you to the tip top boarding-&s;choo<GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="pdcc" EXTENT="1 letter">&punc; Inverne&s;s, kept by Mi&s;s Carolina Killcobeiry?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>JEN.</SPEAKER>
<P>You did, Sir!</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>M'GIL.</SPEAKER>
<P>Tho' your forlorn mother didn't lea<GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="pdcc" EXTENT="2 letters"> you a <HI>bawbee,</HI> (but 600l. which you &s;hall never &s;e<GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="pdcc" EXTENT="1 letter"> <STAGE>(a&s;ide.)</STAGE> &s;o out of pure friend&s;hip, Sandy, there tak<GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="pdcc" EXTENT="1 letter"> her&mdash;off my hands</P>
<STAGE>(a&s;ide.)</STAGE>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>JEN.</SPEAKER>
<P>Dear Sir!</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>M'GIL.</SPEAKER>
<P>Aye, I'm a kind friend Jenny; ain't a gay old fellow?&mdash;Why I'm a &s;econd Robin Gray!</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>JEN.</SPEAKER>
<P>Ah, Sir!&mdash;this la&s;t proof of your kindne&s;s leaves me not a wi&s;h but to know my parents.</P>
</SP>
<Q><TEXT LANG="eng">
<BODY>
<DIV1 TYPE="song">
<HEAD>SONG.</HEAD>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Jenny.</SPEAKER>
<L><HI>Such pure delight my bo&s;om knows,</HI></L>
<L><HI>My thanks are due to Heaven and thee,</HI></L>
<L><HI>With gratitude my heart o'erflows.</HI></L>
<L><HI>Kind agent of his clementy.</HI></L>
<L><HI>Humanity, thou good, &s;upreme,</HI></L>
<L><HI>To Cha&s;e an orphan's tear away,</HI></L>
<L><HI>Like the bright all cheering beam,</HI></L>
<L><HI>Brings comfort from the God of Day.</HI></L>
</SP>
</DIV1>
</BODY>
</TEXT></Q>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>M'GIL.</SPEAKER>
<P>Hey! yonder's a boat put in from th<GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="pdcc" EXTENT="2 letters"> &s;hip in the Offing&mdash;&s;ome great &s;trangers landed.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>SAN.</SPEAKER>
<P>Red coats.</P>
</SP>
<STAGE><HI>Enter</HI> Shelty <HI>with a letter.</HI></STAGE>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>SHEL.</SPEAKER>
<P>A little drummer boy de&s;ired me to give you this.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>M'GIL.</SPEAKER>
<P>You bu&s;y&mdash;cou'dn't he have found any one el&s;e to carry me a me&s;&s;age, than &s;uch a&mdash;you are a bad man!</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<PB N="17" REF="15">
<SPEAKER>SHEL.</SPEAKER>
<P>The letter, Sir&mdash;</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>M'GIL.</SPEAKER>
<P>Seems a &s;mall running hand.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>SHEL.</SPEAKER>
<P>Running! then &s;addle your no&s;e, and run after it.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>M'GIL.</SPEAKER>
<STAGE>(Puts on his &s;pectacles and reads)</STAGE>
<STAGE>(<HI>Sandy</HI> and <HI>Jenny</HI> retire up.)</STAGE>
<P>"Mr. M'Gilpin, The Gentleman that delivers you this"&mdash;</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>SHEL.</SPEAKER>
<P>Gentleman! that's me.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>M'GIL. </SPEAKER>
<STAGE>(Reads)</STAGE>
<P>"is a &s;oldier."</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>SHEL.</SPEAKER>
<P>Not me.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>M'GIL. </SPEAKER>
<STAGE>(Reads)</STAGE>
<P>"commands a company in my regiment." And who is your&s;elf?</P>
<STAGE>(looks at the bottom and reads.)</STAGE>
<STAGE>"<HI>Robert Donald".</HI></STAGE>
<P>Oh, dear! why Jenny, Sandy!</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>SHEL.</SPEAKER>
<P>Well, Sir?&mdash;</P>
<STAGE>(looks at M'Gilpin officious and inqui&s;itive.)</STAGE>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>M'GIL.</SPEAKER>
<P>Get along, you bu&s;y impudent&mdash;Why here, young Laird Donald's gone into the army.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>SAN.</SPEAKER>
<P>Indeed!&mdash;</P>
<STAGE>looks at the letter.</STAGE>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>M'GIL.</SPEAKER>
<P>Stay&mdash; <STAGE>(reads)</STAGE><Q>delivers you this, is a gentleman&mdash;&s;oldier&mdash;company&mdash;my regiment.&mdash;His name is Captain Da&s;h, I have di&s;patch'd him and Serjeant Jack, to rai&s;e recruits in the I&s;le of Col. which my father has made me a pre&s;ent of&mdash;</Q> So then young Robert is our landlord. <STAGE>(Reads)</STAGE><Q>I de&s;ire you will give him all the a&s;&s;i&s;tance in your power, get him as many good men as you can&mdash;</Q> you'll go&mdash;</P>
<STAGE>(to Shelty.)</STAGE>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>SHEL.</SPEAKER>
<P>You know I'am a bad man.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>M'GIL.</SPEAKER>
<P>Plague on the hand! <STAGE>(reads)</STAGE><Q>He's a friend I e&s;teem, therefore every civility you &s;hew him, will oblige yours,</Q></P>
</SP>
<STAGE><Q><HI>Robert Donald.</HI></Q></STAGE>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>SAN.</SPEAKER>
<P>This is the fir&s;t I heard of young Laird Do|nald's being in the army.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>M'GIL.</SPEAKER>
<P>Oh, I mu&s;t dre&s;s, to meet and welcome this Captain, with one of my mo&s;t elegant orations.</P>
</SP>
<STAGE>Exit.</STAGE>
<SP>
<PB N="18" REF="16">
<SPEAKER>SHEL.</SPEAKER>
<STAGE>(Calling.)</STAGE>
<P>Charley! get Mr. M'Gilpin's Sunday coat, bru&s;h his three cock'd beaver, and powder his &s;cratch.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>SAN.</SPEAKER>
<P>I mu&s;t gather all the lads, to make a hand|&s;ome wedding proce&s;&s;ion to the kirk, Jenny.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>JEN.</SPEAKER>
<P>And I to a&s;&s;emble the la&s;&s;es. Oh, Sandy! here, as the packer's in, will you &s;ee if there's any letter for me, as I de&s;ired the lottery man to &s;end me notice, if this chance &s;hould be drawn a prize.</P>
</SP>
<STAGE>(gives it him.)</STAGE>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>SAN.</SPEAKER>
<P>Ha, ha, ha! you never told me you had bought a lottery chance, but it mu&s;t, it &s;hall be a prize, I'll keep it &s;afe for you&mdash;this day proves I'm a favourite of fortune, and &s;he &s;hall &s;mile upon my Jenny.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>SHEL.</SPEAKER>
<P>Huzza, for good fortune! now the&s;e &s;oldiers are come, I may have the rendezvous at my hou&s;e&mdash;&s;o now to &s;inge the &s;heep's head, bake the bonnocks, tap a barrel, and tune my chaunter! and then your wedding, Tol, lol, lol! high do|ings!</P>
</SP>
<Q><TEXT LANG="eng">
<BODY>
<DIV1 TYPE="song">
<HEAD>AIR. <HI>Trio.</HI> Sandy, Jenny, <HI>and</HI> Shelty.</HEAD>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Jen.</SPEAKER>
<L><HI>Excu&s;e a fond maiden's confe&s;&s;ion,</HI></L>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Shel.</SPEAKER>
<L><HI>Her blu&s;hes exhibit her bli&s;s,</HI></L>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>San.</SPEAKER>
<L><HI>My joy is too great for expre&s;&s;ion,</HI></L>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Shel.</SPEAKER>
<L><HI>Suppo&s;e then you &s;peak in a ki&s;s;</HI></L>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Jen.</SPEAKER>
<L><HI>Affections mo&s;t pure now unite us,</HI></L>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>San.</SPEAKER>
<L><HI>Cha&s;te plea&s;ures now wait to delight us;</HI></L>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Shel.</SPEAKER>
<L><HI>The mu&s;ic and bottle I'll bring,</HI></L>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Jen.</SPEAKER>
<L><HI>The finch and the linet invite us,</HI></L>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Shel.</SPEAKER>
<L><HI>Fond turtles &s;hou'd pair in the &s;pring.</HI></L>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Cho.</SPEAKER>
<L><HI>Affections mo&s;t pure, &amp;c.</HI></L>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>San.</SPEAKER>
<L><HI>Let la&s;&s;es pur&s;ue your example,</HI></L>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Jen.</SPEAKER>
<L><HI>The youths may take pattern by thee,</HI></L>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Shel.</SPEAKER>
<L><HI>You give me of love &s;uch a &s;ample,</HI></L>
<L><HI>Oh, married I'll certainly be.</HI></L>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Jen.</SPEAKER>
<L><HI>Oh, what is the gay blooming flow'r,</HI></L>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>San.</SPEAKER>
<L><HI>The tran&s;ient &s;weets of the hour,</HI></L>
</SP>
<SP>
<PB N="19" REF="17">
<SPEAKER>Both.</SPEAKER>
<L><HI>Compared to the charms of the mind;</HI></L>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Shel.</SPEAKER>
<L><HI>Good humour to charm has the power,</HI></L>
<L><HI>To her time leaves no beauties behind.</HI></L>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Cho.</SPEAKER>
<L><HI>Oh what is the gay blooming flower, &amp;c.</HI></L>
</SP>
</DIV1>
</BODY>
</TEXT></Q>
<STAGE>Exeunt Jen. San. and Shel.</STAGE>
<STAGE>Scene an open Country&mdash;<HI>Shelty</HI>'s Hou&s;e.</STAGE>
<STAGE>Captain Da&s;h <HI>and</HI> Serjeant Jack <HI>di&s;cover'd.</HI></STAGE>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>BOTH.</SPEAKER>
<P>Ha, ha, ha!</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>SERJ.</SPEAKER>
<P>Yes, the letter you &s;ent by little Tom &s;he drummer, has prepar'd the old tax-man, ha, ha, ha! he hasn't a doubt but you're a real Captain in the army. Ha, ha, ha!</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>CAP.</SPEAKER>
<P>Ha, ha, ha! and my &s;ole commi&s;&s;ion only the promi&s;e of a pair of colours in the Ea&s;t India &s;ervice, on condition I can rai&s;e an hundred men, ha, ha, ha!</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>SERJ.</SPEAKER>
<P>Ha, ha, ha! Ay, by this &s;ham of pre|tending their young Laird is our Colonel, from the affection of a Scotch Highlander to his Chieftain, I'll warrant they'll flock to our &s;tandard&mdash;and yet, now, tho' 'tis I that have brought you here to the field of action, &s;omething whi&s;pers here, <STAGE>(points to his heart.)</STAGE> Friend Jack, don't impo&s;e upon the&s;e hone&s;t innocent people.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>CAP.</SPEAKER>
<P>P&s;haw! nothing's an impo&s;ition till found out; and our's cannot before we have got our num|ber of recruits, and &s;hipp'd them off&mdash;you know we're certain their young Laird is in England, learning the newe&s;t fa&s;hion of &s;owing oats! ha, ha, ha! and his father, the old Laird, in London, in full cry after jobs and places! from neither ever re&s;iding here on their e&s;tate, our impo&s;ition can't be ea&s;ily detected.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>SERJ.</SPEAKER>
<P>We know our ground, and the character of old M'Gilpin&mdash;flatter his eloquence, and pro|mi&s;e him an agency, and we have every man in the I&s;land.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<PB N="20" REF="18">
<SPEAKER>CAP.</SPEAKER>
<P>Damme! I'd rather have one pretty wo|man, I &s;aw ju&s;t now, than the honour of planting my &s;tandard on the walls of Belgrade.</P>
</SP>
<STAGE>(A loud laugh of Pea&s;ants.)</STAGE>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>SERJ.</SPEAKER>
<P>Some country gambols going forward.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>CAP.</SPEAKER>
<P>The time to recruit&mdash;introduce your&s;elf to them&mdash;&s;et'em on to drink and play cards.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>SERJ.</SPEAKER>
<P>Right&mdash;for when the poor devils &s;en&s;es and money &s;lip off, honour glitters on a bayonet, and riches jingles in a Briti&s;h &s;hilling.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>SHEL. </SPEAKER>
<STAGE>(Without.)</STAGE>
<P>Come along, boys!</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>CAP.</SPEAKER>
<P>To'em, Jack&mdash;coax, wheedle, drink, &s;wear &mdash;zounds! make'em&mdash;</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>SERJ.</SPEAKER>
<P>As wicked as our&s;elves.</P>
</SP>
<STAGE><HI>Enter</HI> Shelty <HI>playing the Pipes before &s;ome Country Lads.</HI></STAGE>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>SHEL.</SPEAKER>
<P>Ay, lads, I think we'll honour Sandy's wedding; but the la&s;&s;es mu&s;tn't &s;et out for kirk before us.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>SERJ.</SPEAKER>
<P>Ha, my hearties! my hone&s;t lad, &s;hake hands</P>
<STAGE>(to Shel.)</STAGE>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>SHEL.</SPEAKER>
<P>Every man &s;hake his own hand.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>SERJ.</SPEAKER>
<P>Why, you all &s;eem very merry, to-day.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>SHEL.</SPEAKER>
<P>Yes, and we'll be merry to-morrow, ha, ha, ha! and we were merry ye&s;terday, ha, ha, ha!</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>SERJ.</SPEAKER>
<P>Ha, ha, ha! why, you're a plea&s;ant fel|low!</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>SHEL.</SPEAKER>
<P>Ha, ha, ha! yes, I am, ha, ha, ha!&mdash;I was born laughing, in&s;tead of crying, my mother laugh'd out, ha, ha, ha!&mdash;my daddy lik'd to have drop'd me out of his arms on the floor, laughing at me, ha, ha, ha! What's the child's name, &s;aid the Par&s;on that chri&s;ten'd me, Shelty &s;ays my God|daddy, ha, ha, ha! then the Par&s;on laugh'd, ha, ha, ha! Amen, &s;ays the Clerk, ha, ha, ha! &s;ince that moment, every body has laugh'd at me, ha, ha, ha! and I have laugh'd at every body, ha, ha, ha!</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<PB N="21" REF="19">
<SPEAKER>SERJ.</SPEAKER>
<P>Ha, ha, ha! I &s;hould like to enli&s;t &s;uch a plea&s;ant fellow&mdash;your good humour wou'd keep us in &s;uch &s;pirits, you'd be the drum of the corps.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>SHEL.</SPEAKER>
<P>Yes, and your rattan would be the drum|&s;tick of the corps, to beat the travally on my back, row dy dow!&mdash;a good morning to you.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>SERJ.</SPEAKER>
<P>I tell you you'd make a develi&s;h good &s;oldier.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>SHEL.</SPEAKER>
<P>That's more than my daddy cou<GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="pdcc" EXTENT="1 letter">d.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>SERJ.</SPEAKER>
<P>Ha, ha, ha! you're an odd fi&s;h!</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>SHEL.</SPEAKER>
<P>Yes, but I won't be a red herring.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>SERJ.</SPEAKER>
<P>No, but you're a pickl'd one tho'&mdash;but pray what are you?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>SHEL.</SPEAKER>
<P>Me! I'm a merchant, and a brogue-ma|ker &mdash;I &s;ells a horn of malt&mdash;moreover, I'm a famous piper. My father. Mr. Croudy, is a necromancer&mdash;he's the gift of &s;econd &s;ight; and Mrs. Cummins, my granny, was bani&s;hed for a witch&mdash;and now pray, who are you?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>SERJ.</SPEAKER>
<P>I'm Serjeant Jack&mdash;in the company of Captain Da&s;h.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>SHEL.</SPEAKER>
<P>Serjeant Jack, you keep company with Captain Da&s;h&mdash;good bye to you worthy Sir&mdash;</P>
<STAGE>(going)</STAGE>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>SERJ.</SPEAKER>
<P>But &s;top, you know your young Laird is our Colonel&mdash;this halbert is his &s;tandard&mdash;do you pay no re&s;pect to it?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>SHEL.</SPEAKER>
<P>Re&s;pect!&mdash;Oh, I beg pardon&mdash;</P>
<STAGE>(takes off his hat and makes a low how to the halbert&mdash;and then turns to go off.)</STAGE>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>SERJ.</SPEAKER>
<P>Ha! ha! ha! very polite indeed&mdash;but &s;top&mdash;</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>SHEL.</SPEAKER>
<P>I mu&s;t tune my chaunter.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>SERJ.</SPEAKER>
<P>Any particular fe&s;tival to-day?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>SHEL.</SPEAKER>
<P>A wedding and here's the bridegroom.</P>
</SP>
<STAGE><HI>Enter</HI> Sandy <HI>and</HI> Countrymen.</STAGE>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>SAN.</SPEAKER>
<P>Come lads, quick! quick!&mdash;Shelty play up&mdash;we mu&s;t march two an two, till we join my Jenny and the la&s;&s;es!</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>SERJ.</SPEAKER>
<P>Ah! I could put you all in the neate&s;t method of marching&mdash;</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<PB N="22" REF="20">
<SPEAKER>SAN.</SPEAKER>
<P>Yes, Sir, but your marching differs from ours&mdash;you march to face enemies, we to meet friends&mdash;you to a&s;&s;ault a town, we to attack a wed|ding dinner.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>SERJ.</SPEAKER>
<P>Dinner! ah! my heroes! England's the field for a trencher battle&mdash;there our drum head is an oak table, Sir Loin leads the van, our right and left wing are a goo&s;e and turkey&mdash;our balls are plum|puddings &mdash;our bullets &s;hot from a dam&s;en-tart; we poi&s;e our knives, handle our forks, then &s;moke &s;lap da&s;h, cut thro' thick and thin&mdash;</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>SHEL.</SPEAKER>
<P>But don't you &s;ay grace?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>SERJ.</SPEAKER>
<P>Yes, my grace is a b<GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="pdcc" EXTENT="1 letter">mper of cherry bounce.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>SAN.</SPEAKER>
<P>Well, ha! ha! ha! come to dinner with me to-day&mdash;and tho' in the Highlands of Scotland, you &s;hall find we talk like French, eat like Engli&s;h, and drink like Iri&s;h farmers.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>SERJ.</SPEAKER>
<P>Ha! well &s;aid my lad! you de&s;erve en|couragement &mdash;I've a rough guinea here, and egad I'll make one at your wedding, to drink my King's health, and &s;ucce&s;s to the young couple.</P>
</SP>
<Q><TEXT LANG="eng">
<BODY>
<DIV1 TYPE="song">
<HEAD>SONG.</HEAD>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Serjeant <HI>and</HI> Chorus.</SPEAKER>
<L><HI>For Soldiers the fea&s;t prepare,</HI></L>
<L><HI>Who friends protect, and foes annoy,</HI></L>
<L><HI>What war has won, let's now enjoy,</HI></L>
<L><HI>Good cheer bright mirth be&s;towing,</HI></L>
<L><HI>Sir Lo<GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="pdcc" EXTENT="2 letters"> fir&s;t we'll nobly dare,</HI></L>
<L><HI>Our ho&s;t looks round his table,</HI></L>
<L><HI>His brea&s;t with friend&s;hip glowing;</HI></L>
<L><HI>We jovial lads whil&s;t able,</HI></L>
<L><HI>Re&s;olv'd to do all honour to the donor,</HI></L>
<L><HI>With courage charge his boil'd and roa&s;t,</HI></L>
<L><HI>In goblets large each toa&s;t,</HI></L>
<L><HI>With &s;park'ling bumpers flowing.</HI></L>
<L><PB N="23" REF="21"><HI>Let drums beat, and fifes &s;ound &s;hrill,</HI></L>
<L><HI>Ye Clarions lend your &s;weete&s;t notes,</HI></L>
<L><HI>Ye trumpets rend your &s;ilver throats,</HI></L>
<L><HI>Proclaim in warlike mea&s;ure,</HI></L>
<L><HI>When the ro&s;y bowl we fill,</HI></L>
<L><HI>The fair &s;hall do their duty,</HI></L>
<L><HI>And &s;ip its b<GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="pdcc" EXTENT="1 letter">l<GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="pdcc" EXTENT="1 letter">ny trea&s;ure,</HI></L>
<L><HI>Touched by the lip of beauty;</HI></L>
<L><HI>'Tis now a draught for Hector, 'tis nector,</HI></L>
<L><HI>The Gods delight, here's wine and love,</HI></L>
<L><HI>Like Mars who fight, &s;hou'd ki&s;s 'like Jove,</HI></L>
<L><HI>By turns the &s;oldiers plea&s;ure.</HI></L>
</SP>
</DIV1>
</BODY>
</TEXT></Q>
<STAGE>Exeunt,</STAGE>
<TRAILER>END OF THE FIRST ACT.</TRAILER>
</DIV2>
<DIV2 N="2" TYPE="act">
<PB N="24" REF="22">
<HEAD>ACT II.</HEAD>
<STAGE>SCENE I. <HI>Cut Wood.</HI></STAGE>
<STAGE>Jenny <HI>and</HI> Girls <HI>di&s;covered laughing.</HI></STAGE>
<STAGE><HI>Enter</HI> Captain Da&s;h.</STAGE>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>CAPTAIN.</SPEAKER>
<P>EH! faith a buxom group, and the very charmer that pleas'd me &s;o much.</P>
<STAGE>(Retires.)</STAGE>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>JEN.</SPEAKER>
<P>True, but no matter whether you are all in white.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>1&s;t GIRL.</SPEAKER>
<P>Ay, but we &s;hou'd for a wedding.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>JEN.</SPEAKER>
<P>You, Su&s;an, and Peggy, are to be my bride-maids; I hope &s;oon to do as much for you.</P>
</SP>
<STAGE><HI>Enter</HI> Moggy.</STAGE>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>MOG.</SPEAKER>
<P>The &s;ooner the better, ha, ha, ha!</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>JEN.</SPEAKER>
<P>Why, Moggy, how got you out?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>MOG.</SPEAKER>
<P>Ha, ha, ha! Oh, dear! I've &s;carce breath to laugh&mdash;ha, ha, ha!</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>JEN.</SPEAKER>
<P>Nay, but tell us how did you get out?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>MOG.</SPEAKER>
<P>Ah, that's it&mdash;he, he, he! Charley &s;o over|acted his part, that he lock'd me up in earne&s;t&mdash;ha, ha, ha! When Charley mi&s;&s;es me, he'll act his &s;ur|pri&s;e &s;o natural, that father will place more confidence in him than ever&mdash;ha, ha, ha!</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<PB N="25" REF="23">
<SPEAKER>JEN</SPEAKER>
<P>Ah, Moggy! you &s;et little value upon the <GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="pdcc" EXTENT="2 letters">e&s;&s;ing of a parent, had I one!&mdash;your father is <GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="pdcc" EXTENT="1 letter">ery good to you, and indeed you &s;hou'dn't vex <GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="pdcc" EXTENT="1 letter">im.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>MOG.</SPEAKER>
<P>Ay, but when a hu&s;band's in the way&mdash;<GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="pdcc" EXTENT="1 letter">ow if I cou'd but meet Charley! Come, Jenny, <GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="pdcc" EXTENT="1 letter">here's the bridegroom, and the garland&mdash;the pipes <GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="pdcc" EXTENT="1 letter">nd the par&s;on?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>JEN.</SPEAKER>
<P>Ha, ha, ha! you wild one!&mdash;but love is <GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="pdcc" EXTENT="2 letters">e theme, and the &s;weet birds &s;hall &s;ing a melo|dious accompanyment.</P>
</SP>
<Q><TEXT LANG="eng">
<BODY>
<DIV1 TYPE="song">
<HEAD>AIR.</HEAD>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Jenny.</SPEAKER>
<LG>
<L><HI>What rapture to think on the time I have &s;een,</HI></L>
<L><HI>On May day I fir&s;t &s;aw my love on this green,</HI></L>
<L><HI>So charming his face and commanding his mein,</HI></L>
<L><HI>The King was my lover, and Jenny his Queen.</HI></L>
<L><HI>The garland pre&s;ented by Sandy,</HI></L>
<L><HI>More &s;weet from the waker, 'twas Sandy.</HI></L>
</LG>
<LG>
<L><HI>A &s;ide lock I threw on my lover by chance,</HI></L>
<L><HI>Which &s;oon he return'd with as tender a glance;</HI></L>
<L><HI>My heart leap'd with joy when I &s;een him advance,</HI></L>
<L><HI>And well did I gue&s;s 'twas to lead up the dance;</HI></L>
<L><HI>For none danc'd &s;o neat as my Sandy,</HI></L>
<L><HI>In all things complete is my Sandy.</HI></L>
</LG>
<LG>
<L><HI>Beneath a gay woodbine with myrtles entwin'<GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="pdcc" EXTENT="1 letter">,</HI></L>
<L><HI>On cow&s;lips and violets one ev'ning reclin'd,</HI></L>
<L><HI>So charming a place and a &s;ea&s;on &s;o kind,</HI></L>
<L><HI>He artfully cho&s;e to di&s;cover his mind.</HI></L>
<L><HI>So &s;weet were the vows of my Sandy,</HI></L>
<L><HI>I then exchang'd hearts with my Sandy.</HI></L>
</LG>
</SP>
</DIV1>
</BODY>
</TEXT></Q>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>MOG.</SPEAKER>
<P>Dear! if here isn't the &s;trange officer been li&s;tening to our non&s;en&s;e! he's come to take <GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="pdcc" EXTENT="1 word"> men away&mdash;he is the mo&s;t impudent devil&mdash;</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>CAP. </SPEAKER>
<STAGE>(Advancing.)</STAGE>
<P>A &s;ine flock of chickens, upon my honor.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>JEN.</SPEAKER>
<P>You're not a fox, Sir?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<PB N="26" REF="24">
<SPEAKER>MOG.</SPEAKER>
<P>No, but he takes you for a lamb, <GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="pdcc" EXTENT="1 word"> throws &s;uch a &s;heep's eye at you.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>ALL.</SPEAKER>
<P>Ha, ha, ha!</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>CAP.</SPEAKER>
<P>You &s;eem to be all&mdash;ha, ha, ha! pray don't let me &s;poil the play&mdash;ha, ha, ha! I'll make one&mdash;what is it? If you'd only admit me, you'd find me the merrie&s;t play-fellow, ha, ha, ha! <STAGE>(To Moggy.)</STAGE> You are, upon my &s;oul, a beauteour no&s;egay&mdash;but here's the ro&s;ebud of the boquet, <STAGE><HI>(<GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="pdcc" EXTENT="1 word"> Jenny)</HI></STAGE> Tell me &s;weet, what's your play?</P>
<STAGE>(Take her hand.)</STAGE>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>MOG.</SPEAKER>
<P>A ro&s;ebud grows in an angry bu&s;h, and about fair maids.</P>
<STAGE><HI>(All the girls take hands and danc<GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="pdcc" EXTENT="1 letter"> round him, &s;inging, "A ro&s;ebud grows in an angry bu&s;h, and about fair maids, and about my merry <GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="pdcc" EXTENT="1 word"> all.")</HI></STAGE>
</SP>
<STAGE><HI>Enter</HI> M'Gilpin, <HI>dre&s;&s;ed extravagantly.</HI></STAGE>
<STAGE>All the Girls run off oppo&s;ite &s;ide.</STAGE>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>M'GIL,</SPEAKER>
<P>Hey! is this the recruiting Captain? 'gad, Sir, I &s;u&s;pect you're come to beat up among our wives and daughters, for a regiment of infantry, ha, ha, ha!</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>CAP.</SPEAKER>
<P>Was ever &s;o &s;weet a ro&s;ebud!</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>M'GIL.</SPEAKER>
<P>Ha, ha, ha! Captain, if your Gene|ral &s;aw you like a maypole, and the petticoat re|giment fri&s;king round you, ha, ha, ha!</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>CAP.</SPEAKER>
<P>Who are you?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>M'GIL.</SPEAKER>
<P>I'm young Laird Donald your Colo|nel's Steward, and Collector of his Maje&s;ty's taxes, come to bid you welcome to our I&s;le of Col.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>CAP.</SPEAKER>
<P>Oh, zounds! they've &s;et me all on fire! Your, hand!</P>
<STAGE>(offers his)</STAGE>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>M'GIL.</SPEAKER>
<P>Bu', Captain, what think you of the bride?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>CAP.</SPEAKER>
<P>Bride! Eh! which? who?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>MGIL.</SPEAKER>
<P>She in the white and tartan ribbans.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>CAP.</SPEAKER>
<P>The very charmer going to be married&mdash;'&s;death, that lovely &s;prig to be worn by a clown!</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<PB N="27" REF="25">
<SPEAKER>M'GIL.</SPEAKER>
<P>Clown! Oh, no, I'll a&s;&s;ure you her <GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="pdcc" EXTENT="1 letter">andy is a very clever lad.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>CAP.</SPEAKER>
<P>He mu&s;t not have her.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>M'GIL.</SPEAKER>
<P>Hey!</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>CAP.</SPEAKER>
<P>I'll have her!</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>M'GIL.</SPEAKER>
<P>You!</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>CAP.</SPEAKER>
<P>Oh, yes.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>M'GIL.</SPEAKER>
<P>Ha, ha, ha! This is recruiting! ha, ha, ha!</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>CAP.</SPEAKER>
<P>Demn your grinning, Sir! what d'ye mean?&mdash;Hark'ee, Mr. Steward, put that trea&s;ure in|<GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="pdcc" EXTENT="1 letter">o my po&s;&s;e&s;&s;ion, and what is there I will not do for you?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>M'GIL.</SPEAKER>
<P>Eh! &s;uppo&s;e you tell me what you <HI>will</HI> do for me&mdash;</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>CAP.</SPEAKER>
<P>Eh&mdash;&s;tay&mdash;true, Jack told me the bait to have him. <STAGE>(A&s;ide.)</STAGE> Ay what think you of the agency of our regiment?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>M'GIL.</SPEAKER>
<P>Good picking in an agency.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>CAP.</SPEAKER>
<P>'Tis yours&mdash;&s;ay no more&mdash;I'll &s;ettle that with my Colonel.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>M'GIL.</SPEAKER>
<P>Eh&mdash;oh, no, no, no, I promis'd her to Sandy.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>CAP.</SPEAKER>
<P>Come, come, be a wi&s;e man, that prefers his own intere&s;t to all other con&s;ider<GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="pdcc" EXTENT="2 letters">ions.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>M'GIL.</SPEAKER>
<P>I am a wi&s;e man; and I&mdash;oh, Lord! &mdash;but the wedding's a thing &s;ettled, clothes bought, Par&s;on be&s;poke, young folks wi&s;hes on tip of ex|pectation! dear, poor Sandy'd break his heart.&mdash;Eh! the fine&s;t thought&mdash;but, I &s;uppo&s;e you never &s;aw her, tho'&mdash;you &s;hall marry my mog!</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>CAP.</SPEAKER>
<P>Damn your Mog! I don't want to mar|ry any body.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>M'GIL.</SPEAKER>
<P>No! why I thought Jenny&mdash;</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>CAP.</SPEAKER>
<P>Zounds! Mr.&mdash;think of your intere&s;t.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>M'GIL.</SPEAKER>
<P>Oh, Lord! I always do&mdash;</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>CAP.</SPEAKER>
<P>Such talents as yours, hid here in an ob|&s;cure corner of the world! &s;uch powers of elo|quence! &mdash;a &s;eat in Parliament.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>M'GIL.</SPEAKER>
<P>Why, our Laird is a bright man <HI>there.</HI></P>
</SP>
<SP>
<PB N="28" REF="26">
<SPEAKER>CAP.</SPEAKER>
<P>He bright! a Scotch pebble, to you; yo<GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="pdcc" EXTENT="1 letter"> eloquence once known, mu&s;t command any thing.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>M'GIL.</SPEAKER>
<P>Why, yes, I think once they find ho<GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="pdcc" EXTENT="1 letter"> I <HI>can &s;peak.</HI> I &s;hall get paid for holding my tongu<GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="pdcc" EXTENT="1 letter">&punc;</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>CAP.</SPEAKER>
<P>Boards! Jobs! Committees! The girl.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>M'GIL.</SPEAKER>
<P>Jobs!</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>CAP.</SPEAKER>
<P>A Pen&s;ion! Place and Peerage!&mdash;Li<GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="pdcc" EXTENT="4 letters"> Jenny.&mdash;</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>M'GIL.</SPEAKER>
<P>Pen&s;ion! Jenny's yours; from a Su<GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="pdcc" EXTENT="1 letter">+veyor, I'll be a Commi&s;&s;ioner; if I am a Steward it &s;hall be of the Chiltern Hundreds.</P>
</SP>
<STAGE><HI>Enter</HI> Charley.</STAGE>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>CHAR. </SPEAKER>
<STAGE>(Apart to M'Gil.)</STAGE>
<P>Sir, Sir!</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>M'GIL.</SPEAKER>
<P>Eh! now you puppy, you've let Mogg<GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="pdcc" EXTENT="1 letter"> give you the &s;lip.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>CHAR.</SPEAKER>
<P>No, Sir, have her &s;afe&mdash;but as you fur pos'd, Old Croudy has ju&s;t landed &s;ome run good</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>M'GIL.</SPEAKER>
<P>But where?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>CHAR.</SPEAKER>
<P>With my gla&s;s I &s;aw him hide them: the Creek, behind the North Foreland.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>M'GIL.</SPEAKER>
<P>From his Boat? was't the Swallow?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>CHAR.</SPEAKER>
<P>You know you feiz'd that la&s;t week, it the other boat, the Angel.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>M'GIL.</SPEAKER>
<P>I'll have her and lading!</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>CAP.</SPEAKER>
<P>My dear Sir, that's Jenny.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>M'GIL.</SPEAKER>
<P>I'll have the Angel condemn'd.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>CAP.</SPEAKER>
<P>My Angel condemnd! for what?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>M'GIL.</SPEAKER>
<P>For running brandy and tobacco.</P>
</SP>
<STAGE><HI>Exit ha&s;<GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="pdcc" EXTENT="4 letters"></HI></STAGE>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>CAP.</SPEAKER>
<P>The old fellow's mad&mdash;but he mu&s;t p<GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="pdcc" EXTENT="2 letters">+vent this marriage&mdash;holloa, Sir! Mr.&mdash;</P>
</SP>
<STAGE><HI>Ex<GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="pdcc" EXTENT="2 letters"></HI></STAGE>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>CHAR.</SPEAKER>
<P>Ha, ha, ha! my ma&s;ter goes to &s;eize hi<GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="pdcc" EXTENT="1 letter"> own goods that I &s;tole out of his &s;tores, and hid <GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="pdcc" EXTENT="1 word"> the rocks for h<GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="pdcc" EXTENT="1 letter">m to &s;eek out, whil&s;t I run off with his daughter.</P>
</SP>
<STAGE><HI>Enter</HI> Moggy <HI>(unperceived.)</HI></STAGE>
<P>I mu&s;t run and let her out.</P>
<STAGE>(going.)</STAGE>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>MOG.</SPEAKER>
<P>Dear Sir, won't you wait for company</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<PB N="29" REF="27">
<SPEAKER>CHAR.</SPEAKER>
<P>Moggy! how the plague did you get out?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>MOG.</SPEAKER>
<P>No matter, here I am, and take me while you can.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>CHAR.</SPEAKER>
<P>Hey? Ecod, t<GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="pdcc" EXTENT="1 letter">is is doing things, ha, ha, ha!&mdash;Charming! I've cut out work for your father, on the oppo&s;ite &s;ides of the I&s;land; &s;o I'll run down to the pier, and get the boat ready, and off we &s;kim like curlews.</P>
</SP>
<STAGE>Exit.</STAGE>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>MOG.</SPEAKER>
<P>Make ha&s;te, Charley&mdash;oh! my bonny Charley.&mdash;</P>
</SP>
<Q><TEXT LANG="eng">
<BODY>
<DIV1 TYPE="song">
<HEAD>AIR.</HEAD>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Moggy.</SPEAKER>
<LG>
<L><HI>My father's hou&s;e is neat and nice,</HI></L>
<L><HI>My little garden Paradi&s;e,</HI></L>
<L><HI>My chamber deck'd with trinkums fine,</HI></L>
<L><HI>My Windows grac'd with je&s;&s;amine;</HI></L>
<L><HI>I have a black bird gay,</HI></L>
<L><HI>Oh he's a pretty fellow,</HI></L>
<L><HI>He whi&s;tles &s;weet and mellow,</HI></L>
<L><HI>The live long Day.</HI></L>
</LG>
<LG>
<L><HI>My playful Kid, hand&s;ome pets I've my many,</HI></L>
<L><HI>My wanton bounding wanton fri&s;king Nanny;</HI></L>
<L><HI>Yet I love none half &s;o well</HI></L>
<L><HI>As Charley's gift, my dear Fidell,</HI></L>
<L><HI>My little Fidell, my pretty Fidell,</HI></L>
<L><HI>Bow wow, bow wow, bow wow, bow wow.</HI></L>
<L><HI>Ha&s;te gentle lover, now for you;</HI></L>
<L><HI>Papa, kid, dog, and chick, adieu.</HI></L>
</LG>
<LG>
<L><HI>In town I'll be, my gla&s;s can tell,</HI></L>
<L><HI>A mon&s;terous flaming marry'd belle,</HI></L>
<L><HI>The foremo&s;t in all game&s;ome bouts,</HI></L>
<L><HI>At operas, plays, and balls, and routs&punc;</HI></L>
<L><HI>All in my plumage fine,</HI></L>
<L><HI>Around the &s;marts &s;hall flutter,</HI></L>
<L><HI>About me what a clutter&mdash;</HI></L>
<L><HI>She's all divine.</HI></L>
</LG>
<LG>
<PB N="30" REF="28">
<L><HI>Ther &s;ong, they dance, to plea&s;e me how they caper!</HI></L>
<L><HI>Whil&s;t rivals challenge, huff and vapour;</HI></L>
<L><HI>As birds all welcome here to woo,</HI></L>
<L><HI>For Charley's &s;ake be gone cuckco:</HI></L>
<L><HI>I'll never create my &s;pou&s;ey's &s;hame,</HI></L>
<L><HI>To &s;inge my wings about the flame.</HI></L>
</LG>
</SP>
</DIV1>
</BODY>
</TEXT></Q>
<STAGE>Exit after &s;ong.</STAGE>
<STAGE><HI>Scene</HI>&mdash;Shelty's <HI>hou&s;e in view.</HI></STAGE>
<STAGE><HI>Re-enter</HI> Moggy.</STAGE>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>MOG.</SPEAKER>
<P>Eh! yon's a boat put in&mdash;here's &s;ome of the pa&s;&s;engers&mdash;what a &s;trang looking&mdash; <STAGE>(looking)</STAGE>&mdash;Ha, ha, ha! by the de&s;cription, it mu&s;t be the &s;trange Par&s;on that's expected from Mull, to marry Jenny and Sandy.</P>
<STAGE>(Retires up.)</STAGE>
</SP>
<STAGE><HI>Enter</HI> Laird <HI>of</HI> Rau&s;ey <HI>(as a Par&s;on) a Servant with portmantua following.</HI></STAGE>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>LD. RA.</SPEAKER>
<P>That dwelling, <STAGE>(points to Shelty's)</STAGE> looks like a public hou&s;e.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>SER.</SPEAKER>
<P>It is, Sir.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>LD. RA.</SPEAKER>
<P>Then engage a room, and leave my bag|gage there&mdash;my great coat was comfortable on the water, but on land its cumbr'ous, <STAGE>(takes it off, and gives it &s;ervant;)</STAGE> and lay out my be&s;t perriwig, that I may look decent&mdash;I will inquire for tho&s;e I want, and you may refre&s;h your&s;elf within.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>SER.</SPEAKER>
<P>Yes, Sir.</P>
</SP>
<STAGE>Exit with things into Shelty's.</STAGE>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>LD. R.</SPEAKER>
<P>Here, pretty maiden.&mdash;</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>MOG.</SPEAKER>
<P>Sir.&mdash;What a civil gentleman!</P>
<STAGE>(A&s;ide.)</STAGE>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>LD. R.</SPEAKER>
<P>Do you know one Sandy Frazer?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>MOG.</SPEAKER>
<P>Eh! Sandy&mdash;</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>LD. R.</SPEAKER>
<P>To whom I am to marry one Jenny.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>MOG.</SPEAKER>
<P>Yes, Sir. <STAGE>(Court&s;y.)</STAGE> I am Jenny, Sir.&mdash;I hope he wont find me out <STAGE>(a&s;ide)</STAGE><STAGE>(He views her with attention and emotion.)</STAGE> Lord! I believe he &s;u&s;pects me!</P>
<STAGE>(a&s;ide and confu&s;ed.)</STAGE>
</SP>
<SP>
<PB N="31" REF="29">
<SPEAKER>LD. R.</SPEAKER>
<P>Then 'tis your wi&s;h I &s;hou'd marry you to Sandy?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>MOG.</SPEAKER>
<P>Yes, Sir; marry us as fa&s;t as you can, Sir&mdash;I'm not in a hurry to be married, Sir.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>LD. R.</SPEAKER>
<P>I &s;ee you are not.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>MOG.</SPEAKER>
<P>Oh, no, Sir, my Sandy wi&s;hes it, Sir, and my father, Sir&mdash;</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>LD. R.</SPEAKER>
<P>I did'nt think you had a father.&mdash;</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>MOG.</SPEAKER>
<P>True, Sir.&mdash;I&mdash;I mean Mr. M'Gilpin; he loves me as if I was his own daughter.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>LD. R.</SPEAKER>
<P>Then he has a daughter of his own.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>MOG.</SPEAKER>
<P>Oh, yes, Sir, Moggy&mdash;Mi&s;s Moggy M'Gil|pin &mdash;a very pretty &s;ort of a body, I'll a&s;&s;ure you, Sir; loves me dearly, Sir, only, Sir, &s;he's given to &s;ib a little now and then.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>LD. R.</SPEAKER>
<P>I cou'd wi&s;h to &s;ee Mr. M'Gilpin, and&mdash;</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>MOG.</SPEAKER>
<P>Why Sir, I&mdash;I&mdash;don't magine you can &s;ee him, 'cau&s;e he's gone on great bu&s;ine&s;s, Sir; but, Sir, he left his be&s;t compliments for you, Sir, and reque&s;ts you'd perform the marriage as &s;oon as you cou'd, plea&s;e your reverence, <STAGE>(curt&s;ies.)</STAGE> If Charley was but now here, we might put it beyond the power of father ever to &s;eparate us, <STAGE>(a&s;ide.)</STAGE> Oh, Sir, here comes my Sandy&mdash;now, Sir, you'll&mdash;oh Heavens! my father! <STAGE>(a&s;ide.)</STAGE> Good bye, Sir,</P>
<STAGE>(going.)</STAGE>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>LD. R.</SPEAKER>
<P>But, la&s;&s;y, &s;top&mdash;</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>MOG.</SPEAKER>
<P>Yes, Sir, I'll &s;top&mdash;when I'm out of your fight.</P>
</SP>
<STAGE>Exit, running into Shelty's.</STAGE>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>LD. R.</SPEAKER>
<P>A whim&s;ical &s;ort of a young lady! Oh, here comes her Sandy&mdash;</P>
</SP>
<STAGE><HI>Enter</HI> Charley.</STAGE>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>CHAR.</SPEAKER>
<P>The boat's ready, and&mdash;hey! where has &s;he &s;camper'd&mdash;Sir&mdash;did you &s;ee a young wo|man?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>LD. R.</SPEAKER>
<P>Yes, your Jenny is gone into that hou&s;e.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>CHAR.</SPEAKER>
<P>Jenny!&mdash;I mean&mdash;</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>LD. R.</SPEAKER>
<P>Then, my good Sandy&mdash;I&mdash;</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>CHAR.</SPEAKER>
<P>P&s;haw! I'm not Sandy&mdash;where the plague can Moggy have&mdash;</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<PB N="32" REF="30">
<SPEAKER>LD. R.</SPEAKER>
<P>Well, I thought &s;he meant&mdash;but I'll &s;ee about the marriage, ta&s;te your ale and wedding cheer, and then ferry over to Inchkinneth, where I have three or four more couple to tack together.</P>
</SP>
<STAGE>Exit.</STAGE>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>CHAR.</SPEAKER>
<P>Now this giddy tit, to kick up her heels ju&s;t at the &s;tarting po&s;t! Her father! Zounds, 'tis well &s;he has mi&s;s'd him.</P>
</SP>
<STAGE><HI>Enter</HI> M'Gilpin, <HI>in a rage.</HI></STAGE>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>M'GIL.</SPEAKER>
<P>Fine police! if the King's Officers are to be a&s;&s;aulted in the execution of their duty!</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>CHAR.</SPEAKER>
<P>Ha, ha, ha, <STAGE>a&s;ide.</STAGE> Oh, then, Sir, you've beat old <GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="pdcc" EXTENT="1 letter">roudy?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>M'GIL.</SPEAKER>
<P>No, damn him, but he has beat me! but I'll let the ruffian know, no body &s;hall cheat the King in this I&s;tand, but my&s;elf&mdash;he's a poacher too, goes fowling, grou&s;ing, and cocking; but I'll grou&s;e and cock him! I'll &s;hew him, that in Col I am grand fowler, prowler, and comptroller. His &s;on Shelty have a child of mine!&mdash;my dear Charley take care of Moggy.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>CHAR.</SPEAKER>
<P>She's &s;afe, I'll an&s;wer, Sir.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>M'GIL.</SPEAKER>
<P>Have you &s;een the Captain? I'll give him Jenny, to &s;ecure my preferment there.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>CHAR.</SPEAKER>
<P>I'll &s;et him another hunt, whil&s;t I look for Moggy&mdash;Sir, have an eye to Jenny, the Par&s;on's come, and if Sandy gets a hint of your intention to give her to the Captain, they'll be coupled unknown to you.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>M'GIL.</SPEAKER>
<P>Ods fi&s;h! but where is Jenny?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>CHAK.</SPEAKER>
<P>This in&s;tant gone into Shelty's.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>M'GIL.</SPEAKER>
<P>Run you in, boy, and &s;ecure her, whil&s;t I rai&s;e the po&s;&s;ey after Croudy.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>CHAR.</SPEAKER>
<P>Lord! Sir, Jenny'd never &s;tay with me, you'd be&s;t in and &s;ecure her your&s;elf, and I'll bring the con&s;tables for Croudy. <STAGE>(Moggy looks out at the door)</STAGE> Look, there &s;he is&mdash;after her, Sir.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>MOG.</SPEAKER>
<P>Its me, you &s;ool!</P>
<STAGE>(apart to him, and re|tires.)</STAGE>
</SP>
<SP>
<PB N="33" REF="31">
<SPEAKER>CHAR.,</SPEAKER>
<P>Oh, dear! its Moggy</P>
<STAGE>(A&s;ide.)</STAGE>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>M'GIL. </SPEAKER>
<STAGE>(Going.)</STAGE>
<P>Stop, you, Jenny! I'll have you!</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>CHAR.</SPEAKER>
<P>Stay, you, Sir&mdash;I'll have her&mdash;</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>M'GIL.</SPEAKER>
<P>You! Zounds, you know &s;he'd never &s;tay for you&mdash;here Jenny&mdash;</P>
</SP>
<STAGE><HI>Exit into</HI> Shelty's.</STAGE>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>CHAR.</SPEAKER>
<P>Sent the Wolf after my Lamb! I cou'd hang my&s;elf! What, what is to be done? Stay, as he'll find her in Shelty's, I'll &s;wear it was he &s;tole her out.</P>
</SP>
<STAGE><HI>Enter</HI> Croudy, <HI>and goes into Shelty's.</HI></STAGE>
<P>Odfo! there's old Croudy gone into Shelty's&mdash;I'll &s;etch the con&s;tables upon him&mdash;I know, from his wicked ob&s;tinate &s;pirit, it will be a devil of a piece of work to take him; and in the confu&s;ion he'll kick up, I may &s;till get Moggy down to the water &s;ide&mdash;then weigh anchor, feather oar, blow kind breezes, and adieu to my old ma&s;ter.</P>
<STAGE>Exit.</STAGE>
<STAGE><HI>Scene,</HI> Shelty's <HI>hou&s;e.</HI></STAGE>
<STAGE><HI>Enter</HI> Shelty, <HI>with a mug,</HI> Apie, <HI>with table and chair&mdash;Laird of Rau&s;ey's &s;ervant, with a great coat and port|mantua, with hat and wig in it, which &s;ervant takes out, and lays on the table, and then exit with</HI> Apie <HI>calling behind.</HI></STAGE>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>SHEL.</SPEAKER>
<P>Yes, Sir, I'm here, Sir&mdash;I'm there, Sir&mdash;coming, Sir. <STAGE>(Drinks.)</STAGE> Lord, what nice ale do I &s;ell&mdash;yes, Sir, my hou&s;e is &s;o full&mdash;oh, what a mor|tal fine chance have I to make money&mdash;but father's wrangling with M'Gilpin, will kick down all&mdash;here he comes; now if he hasn't been in &s;ome new combu&s;tifications.</P>
</SP>
<STAGE><HI>Enter</HI> Croudy.</STAGE>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>CROU.</SPEAKER>
<P>Ha! <STAGE>(Takes the mug from Shelty and drinks)</STAGE> Ha! a &s;coundrel! tell me I rob the King! the Cu&s;tom-hou&s;e Officer takes his pay and &s;muggle &mdash;and he's a damn'd bad &s;ervant, indeed, that robs
<PB N="34" REF="32">his ma&s;ter. Boy, M'Gilpin wou'd have &s;eiz'd my boat, tho' 'twas only la&s;t week he claw'd up my other. <STAGE>(Drinks.)</STAGE> Lo&s;t my poor Swallow!</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>SHEL.</SPEAKER>
<P>Shoud'nt have thought as much,</P>
<STAGE><HI>(turning to the mug)</HI>&mdash;</STAGE>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>CROU.</SPEAKER>
<P>This tax-man&mdash;Oh, zounds! I'll&mdash;</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>SHEL.</SPEAKER>
<P>Lord, father! how do you put one out of all &s;orts! here's my hou&s;e full&mdash;there's the Serjeant has got Sandy and all the lads at cards; and here's Sandy's marriage&mdash;and here this new Par&s;on &s;eems a wet clergy&mdash;and then, now your quarrels with M'Gilpin will&mdash;</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>CROU.</SPEAKER>
<P>Go froth your ale, and &s;core double boy,&mdash;I've thra&s;h'd M'Gilpin.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>SHEL.</SPEAKER>
<P>You han't.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>CROU.</SPEAKER>
<P>I've bang'd him, &s;irrah.</P>
</SP>
<STAGE><HI>Enter</HI> Apie.</STAGE>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>APIE.</SPEAKER>
<P>Oh, mercy, Ma&s;ter Croudy! here's the Con&s;tables, and M'Gilpin in the hou&s;e!</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>SHEL.</SPEAKER>
<P>Lord, Lord! you'll be taken&mdash;Apie do you go down and let no body come up&mdash; <STAGE>[Exit Apie.]</STAGE><STAGE>(Sees clothes.)</STAGE> Eh! this is the luckie&s;t&mdash;here &s;tep into this great coat, hat, and wig, the Par&s;on's &s;er|vant left here&mdash;no time for thinking&mdash;do take a fool's advice.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>CROU.</SPEAKER>
<P>Eh!</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>SHEL.</SPEAKER>
<P>If you are taken to jail you go&mdash;do you want to make a riot in my hou&s;e, and give him a pretence to take away my licence? no, do things ea&s;y&mdash;here, quick, quick! <STAGE>(He helps them on with the clothes.)</STAGE> There, the devil a one of them can know you now&mdash;I'll run and get the boat ready&mdash;you're &s;o nicely di&s;gui&s;ed, you may ea&s;ily get to it&mdash;Huh! oh, dear&mdash;</P>
</SP>
<STAGE>Exit.</STAGE>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>CROU.</SPEAKER>
<P>Oh, you cowardly cur! you're no &s;on of mine&mdash;my cudgel is but a&mdash;if I had only&mdash;Zounds! is'nt that my broad &s;word yonder? I made a pre&s;ent of it to this pigeon; but he never
<PB N="35" REF="33">had &s;pirit to u&s;e it, <STAGE>(takes it from over the chimney;)</STAGE> and &s;hall it be &s;aid, that a Highlander &s;neak'd out like a paltroon, with his broad &s;word in his hand? no, no! no di&s;gui&s;e now. <STAGE>(Flings off clothes.)</STAGE> All fair and open&mdash;if they take me, they take me&mdash;they mu&s;t fir&s;t take this, <STAGE>(draws it)</STAGE> 'twas once drawn in what I then thought a right cau&s;e, but ready now to defend my King; tho' I do run a few anchors of brandy to quaff his health, and brin up my children to fight his battles.</P>
</SP>
<STAGE>Exit.</STAGE>
<STAGE><HI>Enter</HI> Moggy, <HI>frightened.</HI></STAGE>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>MOG.</SPEAKER>
<P>Oh, lud! where &s;hall I hide from father If I cou'd &s;tand behind the door, and &s;lip out as he comes in; but what cou'd bewitch Charley to &s;end him after me? If I cou'd but get down to the pier&mdash;what's this, <STAGE>(<HI>looks at clothes,</HI> &amp;c.)</STAGE> Ha! the Par&s;on's &mdash;Ecod I've a great mind to try now if I can't hide my&s;elf in it&mdash;Ha, ha, ha! on they go, ha, ha, ha! <STAGE>(puts them on)</STAGE> and wig! ha, ha, ha!</P>
</SP>
<STAGE>M'Gilpin <HI>and</HI> Shelty <HI>without.</HI></STAGE>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>M'GIL.</SPEAKER>
<P>She is here.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>MOG.</SPEAKER>
<P>Oh, Lord! there's father!</P>
<STAGE><HI>(She mu<GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="pdcc" EXTENT="2 letters">les her&s;elf, and &s;tands &s;till.)</HI></STAGE>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>SHEL.</SPEAKER>
<P>She is not.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>M'GIL.</SPEAKER>
<P>Sirrah! Charley told me &s;he came in ju&s;t now.&mdash;</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>MOG.</SPEAKER>
<P>Did he, indeed!</P>
</SP>
<STAGE><HI>Enter</HI> M'Gilpin <HI>and</HI> Shelty.</STAGE>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>SHEL.</SPEAKER>
<P>She is not, I tell you&mdash;you've done like a wi&s;e man</P>
<STAGE>(apart to Moggy, thinking 'tis Croudy.)</STAGE>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>M'GIL.</SPEAKER>
<P>I'll have the hou&s;e &s;earch'd!</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>SHEL.</SPEAKER>
<STAGE>(To Moggy)</STAGE>
<P>Don't &s;peak, and I'll get you out.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>M'GIL.</SPEAKER>
<P>Where's Jenny? You're a &s;tamp of your father, the old ra&s;cal!</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<PB N="36" REF="34">
<SPEAKER>SHEL.</SPEAKER>
<P>Father keep your temper&mdash;.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>M'GIL.</SPEAKER>
<P>Deliver up Jenny, you &s;coundrel!</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>SHEL.</SPEAKER>
<P>Keep your cudgel quiet&mdash;Oh, Jenny!&mdash;You think me a Devil among the girls&mdash;this morn|ing I was running away with Moggy&mdash;now 'tis Mr. Shelty, Sir, you've been ki&s;&s;ing Jenny!</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>M'GIL.</SPEAKER>
<P>What old fellow's that?</P>
<STAGE>(to Moggy.)</STAGE>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>SHEL.</SPEAKER>
<P>Over the chimney? Oh, that's Lord Lovat!</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>M'GIL.</SPEAKER>
<P>Over the chimney, &s;irrah!</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>SHEL.</SPEAKER>
<P>Yes, that's poor Simon Frazer</P>
<STAGE>(looking towards a print.)</STAGE>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>M'GIL.</SPEAKER>
<P>Simon Frazer! I mean that</P>
<STAGE>(to Moggy.)</STAGE>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>SHEL.</SPEAKER>
<P>Oh, again&s;t the cupboard? Jenny Ca|maron.&mdash;</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>M'GIL.</SPEAKER>
<P>Get along, you audacious&mdash;I mean that, <HI>that</HI> fellow.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>SHEL.</SPEAKER>
<P>Fellow! this? Oh, Sir, this gentleman is the Par&s;on from Rau&s;ey.&mdash;</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>M'GIL.</SPEAKER>
<P>Oh, I beg his pardon&mdash;How do you do, Doctor?&mdash;Oh, true, you come to marry Sandy and Jenny&mdash;ah, that's all up, Sir.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>SHEL.</SPEAKER>
<P>Don't &s;peak to him, Sir&mdash;</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>M'GIL.</SPEAKER>
<P>Damn your bu&s;y&mdash;Sirrah, you are the cau&s;e of my child's pre&s;ent di&s;tre&s;&s;es, you mi&s;creant! I'll&mdash;Ecod, I'll revenge all upon the rogue your fa|ther. Doctor&mdash;Oh! here, Charley has brought the Con&s;tables.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>SHEL.</SPEAKER>
<P>Father, you &s;ee you mu&s;t fight your way.</P>
</SP>
<STAGE><HI>Enter</HI> Charley <HI>and</HI> two Con&s;tables.</STAGE>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>CHAR.</SPEAKER>
<P>I &s;aw Croudy enter here.&mdash;</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>M'GIL.</SPEAKER>
<P>We'll have him.&mdash;There, Charley, you &s;hew the Doctor here to my hou&s;e, whil&s;t the Con|&s;tables and I &s;earch this for Croudy!</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>SHEL. </SPEAKER>
<STAGE>(Apart to Charley)</STAGE>
<P>Do, Charley, take the Doctor&mdash;its my father&mdash;get him off.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>CHAR.</SPEAKER>
<P>What! I help the e&s;cape of a &s;muggler! &mdash;Sir, that's Croudy in di&s;gui&s;e.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>MOG. </SPEAKER>
<STAGE>(Apart to Char.)</STAGE>
<P>It's me, you blockhead!</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<PB N="37" REF="35">
<SPEAKER>CHAR.</SPEAKER>
<P>Moggy again! <STAGE>(A&s;ide.)</STAGE> Come along, Doctor&mdash;</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>M'GIL.</SPEAKER>
<P>No, you old rogue, no collu&s;ion with my clerk&mdash;I know you&mdash;I &s;ee the tip of his no&s;e&mdash;Con&s;tables lay hold of him&mdash;</P>
</SP>
<STAGE>(The Con&s;tables lay hold of Moggy&mdash;Shelty takes the &s;taff from one of them, and beats the other&mdash;Moggy throws off her di&s;gui&s;e, and kneels before her father.)</STAGE>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>SHEL.</SPEAKER>
<P>Keep off! I'll defend my father with my life.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>MOG.</SPEAKER>
<P>Oh, &s;ave my deare&s;t father!</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>M'GIL.</SPEAKER>
<P>My daughter!</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>SHEL.</SPEAKER>
<P>This my daddy?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>M'GIL.</SPEAKER>
<P>My dear child!</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>CHAR.</SPEAKER>
<P>I've done this well.</P>
<STAGE>(A&s;ide.)</STAGE>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>M'GIL.</SPEAKER>
<P>Before I lock'd, but now I'll double lock you.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>MOG.</SPEAKER>
<P>Don't put me again in Charley's care.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>M'GIL.</SPEAKER>
<P>No, I'll take care of you my&s;elf, my dutiful, affectionate&mdash;but, you jade, who got you out?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>MOG.</SPEAKER>
<P>Who, but my dear Shelty!</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>SHEL.</SPEAKER>
<P>I! Me?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>M'GIL.</SPEAKER>
<P>Ay, the&s;e were all your lies&mdash;your Si|mon Frazer's and Jenny Cameron's again&s;t the cup|board!</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>SHEL.</SPEAKER>
<P>But, where the devil can old Croudy be? Egad as I found Mi&s;s Moggy under a great coat, per|haps I may find my daddy under a petticoat.</P>
</SP>
<STAGE>Exit.</STAGE>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>M'GIL.</SPEAKER>
<P>However, for your concern for me, ju&s;t now, you &s;hall &s;ee me reward de&s;ert, and&mdash;</P>
</SP>
<STAGE><HI>Enter</HI> Jenny <HI>and</HI> Sandy.</STAGE>
<P>Give Jenny to&mdash;</P>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>SAND.</SPEAKER>
<P>Good Sir&mdash;</P>
</SP>
<STAGE><HI>Enter</HI> Captain Da&s;h.</STAGE>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>M'GIL.</SPEAKER>
<P>To Captain Da&s;h.</P>
<STAGE>(&s;tands her to him.)</STAGE>
</SP>
<SP>
<PB N="38" REF="36">
<SPEAKER>CAP.</SPEAKER>
<P>Sir, you &s;hall be a great man, upon in, honour!</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>SAN.</SPEAKER>
<P>Sir, hav'n't I your promi&s;e?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>M'GIL.</SPEAKER>
<P>Eh! Egad I believe I'm a great man al|ready, for I totally forget my promi&s;e.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>SAN.</SPEAKER>
<P>But, Sir, I hold you to that promi&s;e, and with my life I'll ju&s;tify my preten&s;ions here.</P>
<STAGE>(Takes her hand.)</STAGE>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>JEN.</SPEAKER>
<P>Nay, My Sandy,</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>CAP.</SPEAKER>
<P>Hark'ee, young bull calf, if you've a life to &s;pare, in my regiment, it may &s;erve your King and country.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>SAN.</SPEAKER>
<P>Sir, the officer that cou'd di&s;grace his pro|fe&s;&s;ion, by injuring the individual, will prove but a poor protector to his country, and is unworthy the favour of his King.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>CAP.</SPEAKER>
<P>A &s;pirited &s;ort of a &s;coundrel this!&mdash;Old one, I mu&s;t have him.</P>
<STAGE>(Apart to M'Gil.)</STAGE>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>M'GIL.</SPEAKER>
<P>You &s;hall. <STAGE>Apart to him.)</STAGE> Sandy&mdash;remember my agency, tho'&mdash;I &s;ay, Sandy, upon re|collection, I can't a&s;&s;ign over a leafs of the farm I promis'd you, unle&s;s you immediately pay me down a fine of 50l.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>SAN.</SPEAKER>
<P>You know 'tis impo&s;&s;ible for me to rai&s;e &s;uch a &s;um.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>M'GIL.</SPEAKER>
<P>I do. <STAGE>(A&s;ide.)</STAGE> Oh, Lord! can't you? I'm &s;o &s;orry&mdash;but you mu&s;t quit the premi&s;es.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>SAN.</SPEAKER>
<P>No indulgence&mdash;no con&s;ideration for the &s;ervices I have render'd the e&s;tate?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>M'GIL.</SPEAKER>
<P>Indulgence! Sandy!&mdash;I thought you was as hone&s;t as&mdash;as my&s;elf; but now I &s;ee you'd have me turn an unfaithful Steward.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>SAN.</SPEAKER>
<P>You're a wretch! a little mean petty tyrant! and may every unfaithful &s;ervant, who, like you, u&s;es his delegated power to oppre&s;s the poor, and bring cur&s;es on the name of a worthy ma&s;ter, meet the villain's reward&mdash;&s;hame and puni&s;hment!</P>
</SP>
<STAGE>Exit.</STAGE>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>M'GIL.</SPEAKER>
<P>Damme, you &s;hall go on the forlorn hope for this! Captain, you &s;hall have him.</P>
<STAGE>(In a rage.)</STAGE>
</SP>
<SP>
<PB N="39" REF="37">
<SPEAKER>JEN.</SPEAKER>
<P>After all his labour and toil to improve this country, is my love to be driven thus out of it?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>M'GIL.</SPEAKER>
<P>Come home, you hu&s;&s;ey.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>MOG.</SPEAKER>
<P>Ah, do, father, do lock me up, but don't be &s;o cruel to poor Jenny&mdash;don't&mdash;</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>M'GIL.</SPEAKER>
<P>What are locks and brick walls again&s;t &s;uch an Algerine family as Shelty's? Even the old water-thief, his father, wou'd rob a Bi&s;hop of his butter boats!</P>
</SP>
<STAGE>Exeunt M'Gil, Cap. and Mig.</STAGE>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>JEN.</SPEAKER>
<P>And this the completion of my happine&s;s!</P>
</SP>
<Q><TEXT LANG="eng">
<BODY>
<DIV1 TYPE="song">
<HEAD>AIR.</HEAD>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Jenny.</SPEAKER>
<LG>
<L><HI>The bleak wind wi&s;tles o'er the main,</HI></L>
<L><HI>The &s;eaman trolls his jovial &s;ong,</HI></L>
<L><HI>He'll &s;ee his faithful maid again,</HI></L>
<L><HI>And blith his tall &s;hip rolls along.</HI></L>
</LG>
<LG>
<L><HI>From the ma&s;t head the cliff he &s;pies,</HI></L>
<L><HI>His joys in faithful hopes expand,</HI></L>
<L><HI>The tempo&s;t roars, the billows ri&s;e,</HI></L>
<L><HI>In vain he tacks to make the land.</HI></L>
</LG>
<LG>
<L><HI>Relentle&s;s breakers guard the coa&s;t,</HI></L>
<L><HI>His hope, his &s;hip, him&s;elf is lo&s;t.</HI></L>
<L><HI>The bleak winds whi&s;tles o'er the main, &amp;c.</HI></L>
</LG>
</SP>
</DIV1>
</BODY>
</TEXT></Q>
<STAGE>Exit.</STAGE>
<STAGE><HI>Enter</HI> Laird <HI>of</HI> Col, <HI>and</HI> Servant.</STAGE>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>LD. COL.</SPEAKER>
<P>Only enquire if Mr. M'Gilpin is at home!</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>SER.</SPEAKER>
<P>Yes, Sir.</P>
</SP>
<STAGE>Exit.</STAGE>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>LD. COL.</SPEAKER>
<P>I find my arrival is totally unexpected. &mdash;The moment I &s;et my foot on my little territo<GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="pdcc" EXTENT="2 letters"> here, I found my heart glow with all the regal pride of an ancient Scotti&s;h Chieftain! but no re&s;pect&mdash;no one to&mdash;no attendance&mdash;Who's there?</P>
<STAGE>(With authority.)</STAGE>
</SP>
<STAGE><HI>Enter</HI> Shelty.</STAGE>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>SHEL.</SPEAKER>
<P>Ha, ha, ha! there he has taken her home.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<PB N="40" REF="38">
<SPEAKER>LD. COL.</SPEAKER>
<P>Do you belong to the hou&s;e?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>SHEL.</SPEAKER>
<P>No, but the hou&s;e belongs to me&mdash;what d'ye want?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>LD. COL.</SPEAKER>
<P>Manners!</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>SHEL.</SPEAKER>
<P>I thought &s;o, by your making &s;uch a noi&s;e.&mdash;D'ye want any ale?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>LD. COL.</SPEAKER>
<P>Do you know who you talk to?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>SHEL.</SPEAKER>
<P>Yes&mdash;who are you? Oh, he's one of my father's &s;muggling cu&s;tomers. <STAGE>(A&s;ide)</STAGE> You're a ped|lar.&mdash;</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>LD. COL.</SPEAKER>
<P>How?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>SHEL.</SPEAKER>
<P>Oh, I a&s;k pardon, I did'nt &s;ee your lae'd wai&s;tcoat&mdash;you're the puppet-&s;hew man come to Sandy's wedding?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>LD. COL.</SPEAKER>
<P>Sirrah!</P>
</SP>
<STAGE><HI>Enter</HI> Servant.</STAGE>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>SER.</SPEAKER>
<P>Yes, Mr. M'Gilpin is on the I&s;land, your honour.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>SHEL.</SPEAKER>
<P>Honour!</P>
<STAGE>(Looks attentively at Laird.)</STAGE>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>LD. COL.</SPEAKER>
<P>Inform him his Laird is here&mdash;and I command his immediate attendance.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>SER.</SPEAKER>
<P>I &s;hall, my Laird.</P>
</SP>
<STAGE>Exit.</STAGE>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>SHEL.</SPEAKER>
<P>This Laird Donald?</P>
</SP>
<STAGE><HI>Enter</HI> Laird <HI>of</HI> Rau&s;ey.</STAGE>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>LD. R. </SPEAKER>
<STAGE>(On entering)</STAGE>
<P>Only order my bill.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>LD. COL.</SPEAKER>
<P>The Laird of Rau&s;ey! Why, my good friend, what brings you to Col? and in &s;uch a&mdash;</P>
<STAGE>(&s;urveying his dre&s;s.)</STAGE>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>LD. R.</SPEAKER>
<P>Hu&s;h, my dear Donald? I as little expected to have met with you here.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>LD. COL.</SPEAKER>
<P>But how! what?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>LD. R.</SPEAKER>
<P>You may remember my &s;i&s;ter Evelyn making a &s;tolen match with young Cameron; the lad went for England to acquire wealth, the only qualification he wanted; and my &s;i&s;ter, poor thing! to avoid my father's anger lying in here in Col, died in child-birth, leaving a daughter, of whom I am now in &s;earch.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<PB N="41" REF="39">
<SPEAKER>LD. COL.</SPEAKER>
<P>But your canonicals!</P>
<STAGE>(His dre&s;s.)</STAGE>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>LD. R.</SPEAKER>
<P>Why, Sir, meeting on the road with an old dome&s;tic of mine, who is now in the &s;ervice of a Par&s;on engaged to wed a couple here, I prevail'd on him, for a little ca&s;h, to a&s;&s;i&s;t me in a plan, I, on the in&s;tant conceived, to per&s;onate his ma&s;ter, ha, ha, ha!&mdash;lent me clothes, ha, ha, ha! for I thought, in a feign'd character, if I could di&s;cover my niece, I might unknown my&s;elf, have come to her real di&s;|po&s;ition: If capable of poli&s;h, I'd have &s;natch'd her from ob&s;curity&mdash;but I find &s;uch a&mdash;</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>LD. COL.</SPEAKER>
<P>Oh, then you have found her.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>LD. R.</SPEAKER>
<P>Oh, yes; but my niece, Mi&s;s Jenny, as they call her, may make a good farmer's wi&s;e, and in a young fellow, one Sandy, from his character, &s;he's likely to have a mo&s;t excellent hu&s;band&mdash;Ha, ha, ha! &s;uppo&s;ing me the Par&s;on, ju&s;t now, &s;he wou'd have me marry her to him! Ay, &s;he may grace a dairy, and &s;o may be much happier than bringing her into a &s;phere her ru&s;tic education has render'd her unfit for; &s;o I &s;hall give the lad &s;ome ca&s;h with her; but I &s;han't <HI>di&s;cover my&s;elf.</HI>&mdash;And now for your affair.&mdash;</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>LD. COL.</SPEAKER>
<P>I've given this I&s;land to my &s;on Robert&mdash;parted with him la&s;t in London; he had then but ju&s;t return'd from Hamp&s;hire, and the &s;hooting &s;ea&s;on approaching, told me he'd &s;ee what game my new gift afforded; but I don't know how&mdash;I can hear nothing of the boy.&mdash;Fifteen years &s;ince I've been here, &s;o, during rece&s;s of Par|liament, I've taken a trip, to &s;ee if Bob has made any improvements, for his Hamp&s;hire journey had made him a &s;kilful farmer, I a&s;&s;ure you;&mdash;be&s;ides, I was anxious to know how M'Gilpin, my Steward, has gone on: but I hear nothing but complaints of him, and yet the I&s;land wears a fine &s;ace.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>LD. R.</SPEAKER>
<P>Like me, you &s;hou'd come incog, then you'd &s;ee the true face of things.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>LD. COL.</SPEAKER>
<P>Ay, Sir, but no hiding the native dignity of a M'Donald.</P>
</SP>
<STAGE><PB N="42" REF="40"><HI>Enter</HI> Shelty, <HI>very &s;ubmi&s;&s;ively.</HI></STAGE>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>SHEL.</SPEAKER>
<P>My Laird, forgive me taking you for a pedlar.</P>
<STAGE>(Bows low.)</STAGE>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>LD. R.</SPEAKER>
<P>The dignity of a M'Donald!</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>SHEL.</SPEAKER>
<P>Pardon me, Sir, for taking you for a &s;hewman!</P>
<STAGE>(Bows low.)</STAGE>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>LD. COL.</SPEAKER>
<P>Ha, ha, ha! well, Sir, I &s;hall excu&s;e your apologies&mdash;now for hone&s;t M'Gilpin.&mdash;</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>SHEL.</SPEAKER>
<P>Yes, my Laird, he's as worthy a man&mdash;</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>LD. COL.</SPEAKER>
<P>Worthy! I heard&mdash;</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>SHEL.</SPEAKER>
<P>All truth&mdash;he's as great a rogue as ever &s;tood in the picture frame.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>LD. COL.</SPEAKER>
<P>Well, let the gentlemen of the I&s;land attend me.&mdash;</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>SHEL.</SPEAKER>
<P>Gentlemen! Yes, we will all attend your Lord&s;hip.</P>
<STAGE>(bows.)</STAGE>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>LD. COL.</SPEAKER>
<P>And let every one that has any charge again&s;t him appear&mdash;if well grounded, I &s;hall &s;ee him puni&s;hed.&mdash;My Laird,</P>
<STAGE>(to Laird of Rau&s;ey.)</STAGE>
</SP>
<STAGE>Exeunt Lairds.</STAGE>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>SHEL. </SPEAKER>
<STAGE>(Aping Ld. of Col.)</STAGE>
<P>I &s;hall &s;ee him pu|ni&s;hed! hem! a fine thing to be a great man&mdash;hem! call the gentlemen to attend me, <STAGE>(mimicking.)</STAGE> If I was a Lord, what a deal of good I'd do to&mdash;my&s;elf&mdash;I'd, if&mdash;that is &s;uppo&s;ing I was a very great man, indeed&mdash;I'd be the patron of genius and talents, I'd reward the&mdash;&s;tone-eater&mdash;I'd attend all &s;orts of elegant&mdash;cock fights, to &s;hew my good-nature, and to &s;hew my courage&mdash;I'd go to the mo&s;t &s;cientifical academies for&mdash;boxing&mdash;yes, that's it&mdash;the reward of genius now is given to a black &s;mith, or a coal heaver, for a glorious black eye, or a noble bloody no&s;e&mdash;and then there's your concerts, public and private, where &s;ome great Lords play the violin, and others play the fiddle; &s;o, among&s;t tho&s;e fa|mous quality hautboys, who knows how far my chaunter might be e&s;teem'd in polite harmonious jolli&s;ications!</P>
</SP>
<Q><PB N="43" REF="41">
<TEXT LANG="eng">
<BODY>
<DIV1 TYPE="song">
<HEAD>AIR.</HEAD>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Shelty.</SPEAKER>
<LG>
<L><HI>Boys, when I play, cry oh, crimini,</HI></L>
<L><HI>Shelty's chaunter &s;quaker imini;</HI></L>
<L><HI>In love tunes I'm &s;o emphatical,</HI></L>
<L><HI>Fingers &s;haking quivoratical;</HI></L>
<L><HI>With agility,</HI></L>
<L><HI>Grace, gentility,</HI></L>
<L><HI>Girls &s;hake heel and toe,</HI></L>
<L><HI>Pipes I tickle &s;o;</HI></L>
<L><HI>My jiggs &s;till a pate, titilate, pretty mate,</HI></L>
<L><HI>My hop; love mirth, young blood circulate.</HI></L>
<L><HI>Toodle roodle foodle roodle roo, toodle roodle rco.</HI></L>
</LG>
<LG>
<L><HI>Oh, my chaunter &s;ounds &s;o prettily,</HI></L>
<L><HI>Sweeter far than pipes from Italy;</HI></L>
<L><HI>Cro&s;s the I weed I'll bring my tweedle dum,</HI></L>
<L><HI>Striking foreign flute and fidale dumb;</HI></L>
<L><HI>Modern Rizzios &s;o,</HI></L>
<L><HI>Plea&s;e Ma'am's Mi&s;&s;es tho';</HI></L>
<L><HI>Peers can merry &s;trum,</HI></L>
<L><HI>Acts plays very rum,</HI></L>
<L><HI>I'll puff at &s;quare Hanover,</HI></L>
<L><HI>Ca&s;t over, man over,</HI></L>
<L><HI>All the punny pipes from Italy. Toodle, &amp;c.</HI></L>
</LG>
<LG>
<L><HI>I'm in talk a pedant mu&s;ical,</HI></L>
<L><HI>In fine terms I lug intru&s;ical,</HI></L>
<L><HI>Slap Bravura's alt, the rage about,</HI></L>
<L><HI>Hayd'n, Mara, opera, &s;tage about;</HI></L>
<L><HI>Oratorios,</HI></L>
<L><HI>Cramers Florios;</HI></L>
<L><HI>Things at jubilee,</HI></L>
<L><HI>Neither he nor &s;he,</HI></L>
<L><HI>Die at Syren's note,</HI></L>
<L><HI>Tiny threat, petticoat,</HI></L>
<L><HI>This is amateur high mu&s;ical. Toodle, &amp;c.</HI></L>
</LG>
</SP>
</DIV1>
</BODY>
</TEXT></Q>
<TRAILER>END OF THE SECOND ACT.</TRAILER>
</DIV2>
<DIV2 N="3" TYPE="act">
<PB N="44" REF="42">
<HEAD>ACT III.</HEAD>
<STAGE>SCENE I. <HI>A Wood.</HI></STAGE>
<STAGE><HI>Enter</HI> Sandy <HI>and</HI> Jenny.</STAGE>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>JENNY.</SPEAKER>
<P>MY dear Sandy don't grieve; why &s;hou'd ill fortune di&s;turb our tranquility, unle&s;s it cou'd le&s;&s;en our affections.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>SAN.</SPEAKER>
<P>M'Gilpin's de&s;ign of giving you to Cap|tain Da&s;h di&s;tracts me.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>JEN.</SPEAKER>
<P>But he &s;han't; my obligations to him are great, yet this tyrannous attempt to fetter my incli|nations, and a &s;u&s;picion that his motives were not quite di&s;intere&s;ted, have &s;omewhat abated my debt of gratitude.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>SAN.</SPEAKER>
<P>And here won't let me continue in my farm, without this fine of fifty pounds, &s;o I mu&s;t give it up&mdash;but he laid it on to ruin me.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>JEN.</SPEAKER>
<P>Well, and even &s;o, ain't there other farms, or no farm, cou'd you not be happy with your poor Jenny?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>SAN.</SPEAKER>
<P>My &s;ource of happine&s;s! when mine, I &s;hall e&s;teem you as a friend, re&s;pect you as a wo|man, and adore you as an angel&mdash;be for ever grate|ful for your honouring me with your choice, before &s;o many more worthy&mdash;I'll cheri&s;h you in my heart &mdash;love you 'till death, and protect you with my life.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<PB N="45" REF="43">
<SPEAKER>JEN.</SPEAKER>
<P>When you are my dear hu&s;band&mdash;if you can have faults, to me they &s;hall &s;eem failings, but your virtues I &s;hall e&s;teem perfections&mdash;I &s;hall advi&s;e you with candour, obey you with cheerfulne&s;s, make your home the &s;eat of comfort; yet, if you ever &s;hould quit your door with a &s;rown, my &s;miles of welcome &s;hould meet you at the thre&s;hold!</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>SAN.</SPEAKER>
<P>My &s;weet Jenny! this Captain!&mdash;I cannot think of re&s;igning you to a Prince; but if I truly love you, &s;hould I make you the partner of my mi|&s;erable fortunes?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>JEN.</SPEAKER>
<P>Were you a Prince, I'm &s;ure you'd let me &s;hare your &s;plendour&mdash;therefore I'll follow you, my love, the world over, equally prepar'd to partake of your <HI>good</HI> fortune, or <HI>comfort</HI> you in &s;orrow&mdash;oh, don't deny me!</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>SAN.</SPEAKER>
<P>My dear Jenny!&mdash;</P>
<Q><TEXT LANG="eng">
<BODY>
<DIV1 TYPE="song">
<HEAD>AIR.</HEAD>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Sandy.</SPEAKER>
<LG>
<L><HI>At down I ro&s;e with jocound glee,</HI></L>
<L><HI>Far joyful was the day</HI></L>
<L><HI>That cou'd this ble&s;&s;ing give to me;</HI></L>
<L><HI>Now joy is fled away Jenny.</HI></L>
<L><HI>No flocks, nor herds, nor &s;tore of gold,</HI></L>
<L><HI>Nor hou&s;e, nor home have I;</HI></L>
<L><HI>If beauty mu&s;t be bought or &s;old,</HI></L>
<L><HI>Alas! I cannot buy, Jenny.</HI></L>
</LG>
<LG>
<L><HI>Yet I am rich, if thou art kind,</HI></L>
<L><HI>So priz'd a &s;mile from th'e;</HI></L>
<L><HI>True love alone our hearts &s;hall bind,</HI></L>
<L><HI>Thou'rt all the world to me, Jenny.</HI></L>
<L><HI>Sweet gentle maid, tho' patient meek,</HI></L>
<L><HI>My lily drops a tear,</HI></L>
<L><HI>Ah! rai&s;e thy drooping head, and &s;eek</HI></L>
<L><HI>Soft peace and comfort here, Jenny.</HI></L>
</LG>
</SP>
</DIV1>
</BODY>
</TEXT></Q>
<P>This is the fir&s;t time I ever was convinc'd money was a ble&s;&s;ing.</P>
</SP>
<PB N="46" REF="44">
<STAGE><HI>Enter</HI> Benin, <HI>with a letter.</HI></STAGE>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>BEN.</SPEAKER>
<P>Mi&s;s Jenny, Mi&s;s Jenny, a letter by the boat.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>JEN.</SPEAKER>
<P>A letter for me! who can it come from? <STAGE>(Reads)</STAGE>
<LETTER>
<P>Madam, the ticket, No. 125, of which you purchas'd one-&s;ixteenth at my office, is drawn a prize of 1000l.</P>
<CLOSER><SIGNED>Your humble &s;ervant.
THOMAS TRUMAN.</SIGNED></CLOSER>
</LETTER>
Heavens! what good fortune! now Sandy, you may keep the farm!</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>SAN.</SPEAKER>
<P>Eh!</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>JEN.</SPEAKER>
<P>My lottery chance&mdash;where is it?&mdash;you know I gave it you&mdash;</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>SAN.</SPEAKER>
<P>Did you?</P>
<STAGE>(with emotion.)</STAGE>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>JEN.</SPEAKER>
<P>What's the matter?&mdash;let's &s;ee the paper&mdash;its a &s;ixteenth&mdash;&s;tay&mdash;&s;ixteen fifties&mdash;Lord! you can pay the fine&mdash;and we &s;hall have&mdash;aye&mdash;I don't know how much in our pockets.</P>
</SP>
<STAGE><HI>Enter</HI> Serjeant Jack, <HI>&s;inging.</HI></STAGE>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>SERJ.</SPEAKER>
<P>Eh! isn't this the lad I broke at crib|bage? &mdash;'tis&mdash;oh!&mdash;hah, my worthy! I'm ready to give you your revenge at the broads again&mdash;or any game from lan&s;quennet to tee-totum, ha, ha, ha!</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>JEN.</SPEAKER>
<P>Why, have you been playing cards, Sandy?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>SAN.</SPEAKER>
<P>Eh!&mdash;no&mdash;yes, my love&mdash;I&mdash;I had not the &s;malleft of&mdash;but&mdash;that is&mdash;di&s;traction&mdash;Oh, my Jenny! the die is ca&s;t!</P>
</SP>
<STAGE>Exit agitated.</STAGE>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>SERJ.</SPEAKER>
<P>Poor boy! a generous lad too&mdash;&s;pent his money freely on our recruits&mdash;cards?&mdash;yes, touch'd him for three pounds at Shelty's, be&s;ides a lottery chance.&mdash;</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>JEN. </SPEAKER>
<STAGE>(with emotion.)</STAGE>
<P>Sir, did you win a lottery chance from him?</P>
<STAGE>(agitated.)</STAGE>
</SP>
<SP>
<PB N="47" REF="45">
<SPEAKER>SERJ.</SPEAKER>
<P>Yes, my dear, I&mdash;my dear&mdash;and I'll give it you for a ki&s;s&mdash;damme if I don't!</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>JEN.</SPEAKER>
<P>Sir! was it that number&mdash;but it mu&s;t be &mdash;he had no other.</P>
<STAGE>(A&s;ide.)</STAGE>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>SERJ.</SPEAKER>
<P>The prettie&s;t girl I ever &s;aw&mdash;</P>
<STAGE>(gazing.)</STAGE>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>JEN.</SPEAKER>
<P>I &s;ay, Sir, was that the number?</P>
<STAGE>(&s;hews letter.)</STAGE>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>SERJ.</SPEAKER>
<P>Oh, the number&mdash;the lovlie&s;t&mdash;eh&mdash;a thou&s;and! no, no, my dear, I'm not &s;o lucky as that&mdash;but let's &s;ee&mdash;aye, here it is&mdash;ha, ha, ha!&mdash;eh! 125&mdash;tol lol der lol!&mdash;a lucky dog am I&mdash;</P>
<STAGE>(&s;ings.)</STAGE>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>JEN.</SPEAKER>
<P>Yes, it is it&mdash;my poor Sandy!&mdash;</P>
<STAGE>(bur&s;ts into tears.)</STAGE>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>SERJ.</SPEAKER>
<P>Eh! is this 'cau&s;e the lad has lo&s;t? Zounds! this is the girl he was to have married&mdash;thro' my whole life I've been a petty &s;hifting dog, always on the lurch&mdash;yet, damme if I can enjoy this fir&s;t vi&s;it from good Fortune, as it brings tears into the eyes of a pretty girl!</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>JEN.</SPEAKER>
<P>By the lo&s;s of this, Sandy lo&s;es his farm, and I lo&s;e my Sandy!</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>SERJ.</SPEAKER>
<P>Farm! true, the Captain told me this feat of his &s;eparating two lovers, and get a man turn'd out of bread!&mdash;Captain!&mdash;if he was a General he's no &s;oldier.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>JEN.</SPEAKER>
<P>I &s;uppo&s;e, tho' it was I bought the chance, they won't pay it <HI>me,</HI> as I can't bring it to them.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>SERJ.</SPEAKER>
<P>Aye, the poor fellow was turn'd out of his farm, becau&s;e unable to pay the fifty pounds the old ra&s;cal laid on it&mdash;now this wou'd ju&s;t&mdash;this is the fir&s;t time I ever had it in my power to do a ge|nerous action, and I've a &s;trange curio&s;ity to know how a man feels after one&mdash;a failor wou'd&mdash;and why not a &s;oldier? <STAGE>(A&s;ide.)</STAGE> Look y'e, my la&s;s&mdash;before I knew this bit of paper was worth &s;ixty pounds, I offer'd it you for a ki&s;s&mdash;I'm not quite a Nabob in point of ca&s;h&mdash;but if 'twas worth an 100! I &s;corn to go back of my word to one that can't call me to an account for breaking it&mdash;There's your
<PB N="48" REF="46">ticket&mdash;a ki&s;s was the price&mdash;but tho' my mouth waters, pay it to the lad you love.</P>
</SP>
<STAGE>Exit.</STAGE>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>JEN.</SPEAKER>
<P>Can there be &s;o much worth, where &s;o little is expected? now to impart my joy, and make my Sandy happy as my&s;elf!</P>
</SP>
<STAGE>SCENE II. M'Gilpin'<HI>s Hou&s;e.</HI></STAGE>
<STAGE><HI>Enter</HI> Moggy.</STAGE>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>MOG.</SPEAKER>
<P>Ha, ha, ha! father thinks he has me now &s;ure, but I think if our tru&s;ty Benin, the black, procures me the clothes, as he promis'd&mdash;yes, my kind pappy, I &s;u&s;pect I &s;hall &s;urely &s;lip off from you again&mdash;ha, ha, ha! Oh, here's poor Jenny&mdash;&s;he's as unfortunate in her love affairs as my&s;elf.</P>
</SP>
<STAGE><HI>Enter</HI> Jenny, <HI>much agitated.</HI></STAGE>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>JEN.</SPEAKER>
<P>Oh, my dear Moggy! for ever I'm un|done!&mdash;Sandy is&mdash;</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>MOG.</SPEAKER>
<P>Well, I know father has turn'd him out of his farm.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>JEN.</SPEAKER>
<P>But then he is gone, in a &s;it of de&s;pair, and li&s;ted him&s;elf among the &s;oldiers!</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>MOG.</SPEAKER>
<P>What a fool&mdash;ps'h, make him runaway from them.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>JEN.</SPEAKER>
<P>De&s;ert!&mdash;Oh, the puni&s;hment, if taken, is terrible! be&s;ides, tho' drove to it by de&s;peration, I know his noble &s;pirit wou'd &s;corn to fly from the &s;tandard of his King!</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>MOG.</SPEAKER>
<P>If you cou'd procure a man in his place.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>JEN.</SPEAKER>
<P>The equal of my Sandy! not in Scot+land.&mdash;</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>MOG.</SPEAKER>
<P>Oh, yes, my dear, there's another very good man in Scotland!</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>JEN.</SPEAKER>
<P>I mean no affront to your Charley, my dear&mdash;but I've &s;old my lottery chance, and I'm go|ing to offer the money to the Captain, to &s;ee if he will let him off.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<PB N="49" REF="47">
<SPEAKER>MOG.</SPEAKER>
<P>Money!&mdash;I wi&s;h I had a lottery chance, or &s;omewhat&mdash;here am I going to run into the wide world, and, 'ecod I don't think Charley and I, be|tween us, can mu&s;ter up ten &s;hillings for travelling charges.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>JEN.</SPEAKER>
<P>My poor friend!&mdash;I wi&s;h I cou'd&mdash;</P>
<STAGE>(a&s;ide.)</STAGE>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>MOG.</SPEAKER>
<P>Ha, ha, ha! Jenny, I think you had better offer your&s;elf to the Captain&mdash;ha, ha, ha! I warrant he takes you in his &s;tead&mdash;if not, you mu&s;t, as the &s;ong &s;ays, "Pack up your tatters and follow the Drum"&mdash;you'd make a very &s;mart little &s;oldier's wife&mdash;with a brace of bairns in your arms, and an|other little &s;qaub fat fellow &s;qualling on the knap|&s;ack behind your Caledonian Alexander.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>JEN.</SPEAKER>
<P>Why, my dear Moggy! if it even &s;hou'd come to that, I have a heart prepar'd for all weathers &mdash;yet I doubt my fortitude!</P>
</SP>
<Q><TEXT LANG="eng">
<BODY>
<DIV1 TYPE="song">
<HEAD>AIR.</HEAD>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Jenny.</SPEAKER>
<L><HI>Deare&s;t youth this heart will break,</HI></L>
<L><HI>If cruel &s;oldiers take thee far;</HI></L>
<L><HI>Why peaceful home and me for&s;ake,</HI></L>
<L><HI>To tempt the dangers of the war;</HI></L>
<L><HI>But all is home where thou'lt re&s;ort,</HI></L>
<L><HI>My Sandy's &s;miles &s;uch comfort bring,</HI></L>
<L><HI>The humble Village is a Court,</HI></L>
<L><HI>Grac'd by the pre&s;ence of a King.</HI></L>
<L><HI>My &s;ilken geer I'll leave behind,</HI></L>
<L><HI>Prepare to face the rain and wind,</HI></L>
<L><HI>With him I'll meet the bla&s;t &s;o keen,</HI></L>
<L><HI>And &s;mile while on the billows to&s;t;</HI></L>
<L><HI>The heart where love is warm within,</HI></L>
<L><HI>Enjoys a May in Winter's fro&s;t.</HI></L>
</SP>
</DIV1>
</BODY>
</TEXT></Q>
<STAGE>Exit.</STAGE>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>MOG.</SPEAKER>
<P>My &s;weet gentle Friend!&mdash;my father u&s;es her very unju&s;tly&mdash;I'm certain her mother, for all he &s;ays of her poverty and his charity to her, left the money behind that has been the making of him&mdash;She mu&s;t be come of good people, from her refin'd &s;entiments and elegant manners&mdash;&s;he quite eclip&s;es me; and yet I don't envy, but love her
<PB N="50" REF="48">dearly.&mdash;How long Benin &s;tays&mdash;if he &s;hou'd di&s;|appoint &mdash;perhaps betray me to my father!&mdash;no, here he comes, the faithful fellow&mdash;yes, he has got them&mdash;oh, precious!</P>
</SP>
<STAGE><HI>Enter</HI> Benin, <HI>with bundle.</HI></STAGE>
<P>Well Benin, have you?&mdash;&s;hew, my good&mdash;</P>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>BEN.</SPEAKER>
<P>Yes, Mi&s;&s;y, and I tink dey vil fit you.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>MOG.</SPEAKER>
<P>My be&s;t creature&mdash;</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>BEN.</SPEAKER>
<P>Ah, Mi&s;&s;y! but Ma&s;&s;a lick a me, as I was vor&s;e creature&mdash;Mi&s;&s;y if you run away, I run too&mdash;Ma&s;&s;a kill a me, if he know I help you.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>MOG.</SPEAKER>
<P>P&s;haw! you fool, I'm not going to run away.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>BEN.</SPEAKER>
<P>Mi&s;&s;y, dere Mi&s;s Jenny write letter in par|lour below&mdash;want me fetch it.&mdash;Mu&s;y, pray don't tell Ma&s;&s;a I brought you clothes.</P>
</SP>
<STAGE>Exit.</STAGE>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>MOG.</SPEAKER>
<P>Let's &s;ee what you have brought&mdash;jacket, kilt, bonnet, complete&mdash;I won't even tell Charley of my de&s;ign 'till I'm equipp'd&mdash;ha, ha, ha! I'll &s;ur|pri&s;e him.&mdash;There I'll lay all &s;nug&mdash; <STAGE>(puts the bundle in pre&s;s in the flat.)</STAGE> Now if Charley cou'd borrow ca&s;h to carry us up to Edinbro', father cou'd never find us out there&mdash;let's &s;ee, lud! I hav'n't above half a guinea left of my own pocket money&mdash;Oh, poor Charley and I&mdash;</P>
</SP>
<STAGE><HI>Enter</HI> Benin, <HI>with a letter.</HI></STAGE>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>BEN.</SPEAKER>
<P>Mi&s;s Moggy, Jenny de&s;ire me give you dis.&mdash;</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>MOG.</SPEAKER>
<P>Very well.</P>
</SP>
<STAGE>Exit Benin.</STAGE>
<P>What's this! an Edinbro' bank note for forty pounds&mdash;let's &s;ee&mdash; <STAGE>(reads.)</STAGE><Q>My dear Moggy, for certain the Captain will never part with &s;uch a &s;oldier as my Sandy&mdash;therefore I &s;hall take your hint and 'follow the drum.' As I &s;hall not want the enclos'd, accept it, my dear friend, for travelling charges&mdash;be&s;ides a &s;upply of ca&s;h you will find nece&s;&s;ary 'till you can obtain your father's
<PB N="51" REF="49">pardon for the &s;teps you are about to take, in which be happier than your Jenny!</Q>&mdash;My generous friend!&mdash;no, I will not enjoy happine&s;s whil&s;t you feel &s;orrow!&mdash;With the a&s;&s;i&s;tance of my Highland dre&s;s, here in my cuphoard, if I can once more elope, the fir&s;t u&s;e I make of my liberty is to procure it for your Sandy&mdash;ay&mdash;tho' father catches me the next mo|ment.</P>
<STAGE><HI>Enter</HI> M'Gilpin.</STAGE>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>M'GIL.</SPEAKER>
<P>I'll fir&s;t catch you this moment. <STAGE>(Takes her by the arm, and takes a key out of his pocket.)</STAGE> Go in there.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>MOG.</SPEAKER>
<P>No, Sir!</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>M'GIL.</SPEAKER>
<P>Go in&mdash;</P>
</SP>
<STAGE><HI>Enter</HI> Charley.</STAGE>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>CHAR.</SPEAKER>
<P>What's the matter, Sir?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>M'GIL.</SPEAKER>
<P>Here's a young lady won't be lock'd up.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>CHAR.</SPEAKER>
<P>Oh, fie, Mi&s;s, refu&s;e to be lock'd up&mdash;that's &s;o unrea&s;onable of you&mdash;</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>M'GIL.</SPEAKER>
<P>So it is&mdash;isn't it a proof what value I &s;et upon you, hu&s;&s;y!&mdash;don't I lock up my guineas? you, you&mdash;brazen-face go in there&mdash; <STAGE>(puts her in.)</STAGE> If I &s;hould be obliged to go out, Charley, you will have a watch here</P>
<STAGE>(As M'Gil turns his head to &s;peak to Charley, Moggy, un&s;een by either, &s;lips again out of the door; pulls Charley by the ear, and runs into the pre&s;s.)</STAGE>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>CHAR.</SPEAKER>
<P>Now Sir! what's that for?</P>
<STAGE>(putting his hand to his ear.)</STAGE>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>M'GIL.</SPEAKER>
<P>Charley, don't &s;ay a word again&s;t it&mdash;it &s;hall be as I like with my own family.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>CHAR.</SPEAKER>
<P>Yes, Sir, but when you count ears, pray don't con&s;ider me as one of the family.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>M'GIL.</SPEAKER>
<P>Ay, true, my lad&mdash;however&mdash; <STAGE>(turning to the door)</STAGE>, &s;tay you there, the plague of my fa|mily! <STAGE>(locks the door.)</STAGE> I think I have you fa&s;t now, my deary.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<PB N="52" REF="50">
<SPEAKER>CHAR.</SPEAKER>
<P>My poor girl!</P>
<STAGE>(A&s;ide.)</STAGE>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>M'GIL.</SPEAKER>
<P>Charley, boy, tho' I have the key, yet I &s;carce think I am &s;ure of her, even now&mdash;&s;he's full of hocus pocus&mdash;&s;o, d'ye hear, now and then throw an eye to her door&mdash;that rogue, Shelty, mu&s;t have been a&s;&s;i&s;ted by his grand-mother, the old witch I bani&s;h'd, to have got her out before.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>CHAR.</SPEAKER>
<P>Eh I I'll enourage this thought&mdash;yet not &s;eem to give into it. <STAGE>(A&s;ide.)</STAGE> No, Sir, no.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>M'GIL.</SPEAKER>
<P>Ha, ha, ha!&mdash;well, well, I de&s;y the black art, I depend upon &s;imple wit&mdash;</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>CHAR.</SPEAKER>
<P>Simple, indeed!</P>
<STAGE>(A&s;ide.)</STAGE>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>M'GIL.</SPEAKER>
<P>Charley, I am now going into my &s;tudy to practice oratory&mdash;don't let any body interrupt me, boy! hem.</P>
</SP>
<STAGE>Exit, with much &s;elf-&s;ufficiency.</STAGE>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>CHAR.</SPEAKER>
<P>I find he does'nt know yet that old Laird Donald is come&mdash;ha, ha, ha!&mdash;his ridiculous idea of Shelty's grand-mother being a witch, &s;hews his poor brain is &s;o weak&mdash;and his prejudices of witch|craft &s;o very &s;trong, that his credulity may be ea&s;ily impos'd on&mdash;he is prepar'd to believe any extravagance that may confirm his favourite opinion. If I cou'd make it the means to procure my dear Moggy's re|lea&s;e &mdash;to per&s;uade him that&mdash;ha, ha, ha! I'm ex|tremely tickled with the thought.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>SHELTY. </SPEAKER>
<STAGE>(Without.)</STAGE>
<P>Suppo&s;e he is bu&s;y.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>BENIN. </SPEAKER>
<STAGE>(Without.)</STAGE>
<P>Well, I'll tell my Ma&s;&s;a&mdash;</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>CHAR.</SPEAKER>
<P>And here comes Shelty, in the nick of time, to help my project&mdash;ha, ha, ha!&mdash;I'll try it, however&mdash;ha, ha, ha!</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>M'GIL. </SPEAKER>
<STAGE>(Without &s;peaking to Benin.)</STAGE>
<P>I'll break your bones!</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>BEN.</SPEAKER>
<P>Me don't care,&mdash;oh&mdash;</P>
<STAGE>(crying.)</STAGE>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>CHAR.</SPEAKER>
<P>Hey! what now?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>M'GIL.</SPEAKER>
<P>An impudent &s;coundrel!&mdash;I'll&mdash;</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>CHAR.</SPEAKER>
<P>Here he comes, and in a rare humour for my purpo&s;e&mdash;If I can but make him give her up to Shelty!&mdash;once &s;he's out of the&s;e doots, I have my dear girl.</P>
</SP>
<GAP DESC="missing" EXTENT="4 pages">
<SP>
<PB N="57" REF="51">
<SPEAKER>M'GIL.</SPEAKER>
<P>Out with him, my hero&mdash;you're a clever boy, faith. <STAGE>(Charley throws the &s;tick down, &s;truts about, u&s;es much action, and moves his lips, as it talking.)</STAGE> 'Gad Charley can't &s;peak, he's &s;o very angry&mdash;I never &s;aw him in a pa&s;&s;ion before&mdash;is he gone?&mdash; <STAGE>Charley moves his lips.)</STAGE> He is the knave, to let's come to our&s;elves, and con&s;ider&mdash;call Benin. <STAGE>(Charley turns his face to the door, and moves his lips, as if calling.)</STAGE> Why don't you call him when I bid you? <STAGE><HI>(Charley &s;eems to call, his mouth wi<GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="pdcc" EXTENT="1 letter">e open, but w<GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="pdcc" EXTENT="2 letters">hout &s;peaking.)</HI></STAGE> Zounds, &s;ir ah, call him. <STAGE><HI>(Charley &s;eems to bawl (Benin) very loud&mdash;M'Gil <GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="pdcc" EXTENT="3 letters">ks at Charley, who moves his lips.)</HI></STAGE> Damn the fellow! what's he at&mdash;is Benin coming? <STAGE>(Charley moves his lips.)</STAGE> Eh&mdash;ain't I worthy of an an&s;wer? <STAGE>(Charley &s;eems to &s;peak with much action)</STAGE> Damme, I &s;hall knock you down if you &s;tand making mouths at me, you ra&s;cal! <STAGE>(Charley pau&s;es, &s;eems to mu&s;e&mdash;&s;uddenly &s;tarts&mdash;points to Shelty's &s;tick, then to his own arm, intimating he had been &s;truck with it, and in an agony, bur&s;ts into tears.)</STAGE> Eh!&mdash;why, can't you &s;peak?&mdash;Eh! aye, indeed, I &s;aw Shelty &s;trike him with that fatal &s;tick; but it's impo&s;&s;ible&mdash;it ca'nt be&mdash;&s;peak&mdash;I won't believe but you can&mdash;eh!&mdash;none of your capers upon me&mdash;come &s;peak this moment&mdash;this in&s;tant &s;ay in plain audible Engli&s;h&mdash;how aye do, Mr. M'Gil|pin &mdash;or down you are, as flat as a flounder, <STAGE>(Attempis to &s;trike him.)</STAGE><STAGE>(Charley kneels and &s;upplicates.)</STAGE> Eh&mdash;poor Charley!&mdash;faith if he has really lo&s;t his voice&mdash;I won't believe it&mdash;I'm &s;trangely tempted to try it on my&s;elf; but then when I get into Parliament, if I lo&s;e my voice, I &s;hall be fit only to be the Speaker&mdash;I'll venture&mdash;you Charley, &s;irrah, take up that &s;tick and touch <HI>me</HI> with it, very gently, boy. <STAGE>(Charley &s;trikes him hard.)</STAGE> Zounds, that is enough to knock a man &s;peechle&s;s.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>CHAR.</SPEAKER>
<P>Oh, if I never recover my voice, I'm a mi&s;erable being!</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>M'GIL.</SPEAKER>
<P>Why you have, you rogue, I heard your &s;peak then very plain.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<PB N="58" REF="52">
<SPEAKER>CHAR.</SPEAKER>
<P>Eh! now my ma&s;ter's lips move, as it he was talking.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>M'GIL.</SPEAKER>
<P>Ha, ha, ha!&mdash;why, I am talking, you fool!</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>CHAR.</SPEAKER>
<P>Yes, they &s;till move, but no &s;ound&mdash;Eh! perhaps I may now have recovered my voice, by the &s;tick touching my ma&s;ter&mdash;Oh, true, Shelty told me that the dumbne&s;s was transferrable!</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>M'GIL.</SPEAKER>
<P>Transferrable&mdash;the dumbne&s;s&mdash;what's that you &s;ay, boy?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>CHAR.</SPEAKER>
<P>Eh!&mdash;may be he's not inclin'd for talking.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>M'GIL.</SPEAKER>
<P>Sirrah, I'm always inclin'd for talking.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>CHAR.</SPEAKER>
<P>I'll a&s;k him a que&s;tion to prove it&mdash;Sir, what &s;hall I do with this wand of Shelty's?</P>
<STAGE>(pointing to it.)</STAGE>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>M'GIL.</SPEAKER>
<P>Burn it.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>CHAR.</SPEAKER>
<P>Speak, Sir!</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>M'GIL.</SPEAKER>
<P>I &s;ay to the flames with it; and I believe on a &s;tatute of James the Sixth, I cou'd burn the owner.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>CHAR.</SPEAKER>
<P>Dear Sir! &s;peak if you can.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>M'GIL.</SPEAKER>
<P>Why, I am &s;peaking, you puppy!</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>CHAR.</SPEAKER>
<P>Yes, by the motion of his lips, the poor gentleman thinks he's &s;peaking.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>M'GIL.</SPEAKER>
<P>Speaking! Zounds, I'm bawling!&mdash;I won't believe but I'm heard, &s;irrah, I'll&mdash;</P>
</SP>
<STAGE><HI>Enter</HI> Benin.</STAGE>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>BEN. </SPEAKER>
<STAGE>(Apart to Charley)</STAGE>
<P>What humour is he in?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>CHAR.</SPEAKER>
<P>Shelty has put him in a pa&s;&s;ion?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>BEN.</SPEAKER>
<P>I taught &s;o by his roaring&mdash;I won't an&s;wer whatever he &s;ays.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>CHAR.</SPEAKER>
<P>Don't</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>M'GIL.</SPEAKER>
<P>Now I'll &s;ee if&mdash; <STAGE><HI>(a&s;ide)</HI>&mdash;</STAGE> Here, you &s;coundrel, do you hear me?</P>
<STAGE>(very loud.)</STAGE>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>BEN.</SPEAKER>
<P>Tank you, Charley.</P>
</SP>
<STAGE>Exit, without looking at M'Gil.</STAGE>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>M'GIL.</SPEAKER>
<P>Aye, 'tis plain I can't make my&s;elf be heard&mdash;Oh! I have lo&s;t my voice, <STAGE>(bawling;)</STAGE> but
<PB N="59" REF="53">zounds, it can't be!&mdash;This may be a confederacy&mdash;but hold&mdash;if &s;o, my <HI>daughter</HI> can't be in the plot, as no body could have &s;poke to her &s;ince I lock'd her up here within. True, and even the windows are nail'd down&mdash;I'll &s;ee if &s;he can hear me&mdash;</P>
<STAGE>(unlocks the door, and goes in.)</STAGE>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>CHAR.</SPEAKER>
<P>Oh, the plague!&mdash;now Moggy'll an&s;wer him, and overthrow all my magic.</P>
</SP>
<STAGE><HI>Moggy peeps out of the Pre&s;s.</HI>]</STAGE>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>MOG.</SPEAKER>
<P>Charley&mdash;</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>CHAR.</SPEAKER>
<P>You there&mdash;oh, then&mdash;why, I believe the black gentleman <HI>has</HI> been at work in earne&s;t&mdash;how the duce got you there? and the key, which lock'd you into that room <STAGE>(pointing to the room)</STAGE> in your father's pocket.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>MOG.</SPEAKER>
<P>P&s;haw! you fool&mdash;Hu&s;h! I'm dre&s;&s;ing here, ha, ha, ha!&mdash;why, you're humming him nicely, he, he, he!&mdash;but only get him out of the way, and off we go.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>CHAR.</SPEAKER>
<P>Pop in, here he comes. <STAGE>(Moggy takes in her head.)</STAGE> Now if I can but get him out&mdash;</P>
</SP>
<STAGE>Re-enter M'Gilpin, in a great rage and a&s;toni&s;hment.</STAGE>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>M'GIL.</SPEAKER>
<P>She's gone&mdash;I &s;hall go mad&mdash;he has got her out, but how? no other way but the chimney, or the key hole&mdash;how the devil!&mdash;ble&s;s us&mdash;yes, if Shelty cou'd carry her off, when here&mdash;I found the door lock'd. I can no longer doubt his power to take my &s;peech&mdash;Oh, I'm a mo&s;t mi&s;erable old gentleman!&mdash;I'm in grief, and no body to pity me&mdash;I complain, and none can hear my lamentations <STAGE>(Weeps.)</STAGE> Eh! but hold&mdash;as Charley recovered by my getting the dumbne&s;s, I can as eafily transfer it to &s;omebody el&s;e, and &s;o recover my own voice, ha, ha, ha!&mdash;P&s;haw! except his taking Moggy&mdash;If this is the wor&s;t, a fig for his power, ha, ha, ha!&mdash;I've a great mind to return it again to Charley, ha, ha, ha! but his voice will be nece&s;&s;ary to explain my ac|counts to Laird Donald.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<PB N="60" REF="54">
<SPEAKER>CHAR.</SPEAKER>
<P>Well, Sir, what does Mi&s;s Moggy &s;ay to her lover's tricks?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>M'GIL.</SPEAKER>
<P>P&s;haw! this fool tantalizes me with que&s;tions, when he knows I cant't make him hear my an&s;wers!&mdash;who &s;hall I confer this favour on? Eh&mdash;ay, &s;tupid Benin, the blackmamoor, has little occa&s;ion for his gutteral &s;ounds&mdash;&s;ome revenge too for his in|terrupting my &s;tudies ju&s;t now.</P>
</SP>
<STAGE><HI>Enter</HI> Benin.</STAGE>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>BEN.</SPEAKER>
<P>Sir, here's Laird Donald.</P>
<STAGE>(Very &s;ubmi&s;&s;ive|ly)</STAGE>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>M'GIL.</SPEAKER>
<P>Oh, dear! I mu&s;t recover my tongue to talk him over!&mdash;Yes, I'll give my dumbne&s;s to Benin&mdash;damme, I'll bang you into &s;ilence, my dou|ble dy'd &s;warthy acquaintance</P>
<STAGE>(Takes the &s;tock from the ground.)</STAGE>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>BEN.</SPEAKER>
<P>Tank y'ee, Charley.</P>
</SP>
<STAGE>Exit.</STAGE>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>M'GIL.</SPEAKER>
<P>He has hopp'd off like a black-bird&mdash;wou'dn't even wait till I &s;hake &s;alt upon his tail.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>CHAR.</SPEAKER>
<P>I &s;ee my only method to get him out of the way, is to bring him into di&s;grace with Laird Donald, which, from the complaints of all the te|nants, and the Laird's haughty temper, a little thing will do. <STAGE>(A&s;ide.)</STAGE> Oh, dear &s;ir, yonder comes the Laird, and I believe the whole clan.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>M'GIL.</SPEAKER>
<P>Ecod, then I mu&s;t touch Charlev, for &s;peak to Laird Donald I mu&s;t, and u&s;e a good deal of palavar too.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>CHAR.</SPEAKER>
<P>Now, Sir, what will you do? &s;tay&mdash;od &s;o&mdash;well remembered; Shelty told me one virtue of that &s;tick, whil&s;t its held in the le&s;t hand, a per|&s;on can be heard by every one but the very per&s;on they addre&s;s.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>M'GIL.</SPEAKER>
<P>Eh&mdash;</P>
<STAGE>(with joy.)</STAGE>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>CHAR.</SPEAKER>
<P>Now Sir, you've an opportunity of doing what no body does&mdash;to &s;peak your mind to a great man.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>M'GIL.</SPEAKER>
<P>I never &s;poke my mind to any man.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<PB N="61" REF="55">
<SPEAKER>CHAR.</SPEAKER>
<P>And my dear Sir, in&s;tead of this fine com|plimentary &s;peech which you intended, I would &s;peak boldly to him; by that you may &s;till keep up your own con&s;equence among&s;t the tenants, without incur|ring his di&s;plea&s;ure, as he will be the only per&s;on pre&s;ent that cannot here you.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>M'GIL.</SPEAKER>
<P>I'll abu&s;e him!&mdash;Zounds! what a great bird they'll all think me! for a Highland Chief is a Demigod among&s;t his va&s;&s;als&mdash;ha, ha, ha!&mdash;here he marches in at their head, like a great turkey.</P>
</SP>
<STAGE><HI>Enter</HI> Laird <HI>of</HI> Col, Servant, <HI>and</HI> Highlanders.</STAGE>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>LD. COL.</SPEAKER>
<P>Well, Mr. M'Gilpin, with the remem|brance of my per&s;on, you &s;eem to have lo&s;t all duty for your Laird.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>CHAR.</SPEAKER>
<P>Hem! my Laird&mdash;Collect your&s;elf, <STAGE>(apart to M'Gil.)</STAGE> I &s;ay, my Laird, I have the honour to be confidential Secretary to your Lord&s;hip's Tax-man; and, my Laird, in a mo&s;t re&s;pectful &s;peech, the voice of your whole I&s;le of Col con&s;titute Mr. M'Gilpin their humble mouth.</P>
<STAGE>(Bows.)</STAGE>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>M'GIL.</SPEAKER>
<P>Humble mouth! I didn't think Charley cou'd &s;peak &s;o pretty!&mdash;I'm glad I did'nt unvoice him. <STAGE>(They change &s;ticks)</STAGE> Hem!&mdash;As he can't hear me, I'll give it him on both &s;ides of his ears&mdash;in what <GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="pdcc" EXTENT="1 word"> &s;uperior light they'll all look upon me in future&mdash;hem&mdash;now for it&mdash;off I go! hem!&mdash;Sir, you Do|nald, here&mdash;in the name of the a&s;&s;embly pre&s;ent, and the i&s;land in general, I tell you, you are an op|pre&s;&s;ive up&s;tart&mdash;in a word, you are a proud old puppy!</P>
<STAGE>(Smiling, and u&s;ing the action of &s;ervile adula|tion.)</STAGE>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>LD. COL.</SPEAKER>
<P>Hey!</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>M'GIL.</SPEAKER>
<P>He's &s;urpis'd I don't &s;peak; and they are all &s;truck with wonder at what I do&mdash;Ecod I'll at him again, <STAGE>(a&s;ide.)</STAGE> Eh! and &s;o you've got into Par|liament? &mdash;a pretty repre&s;entative of the people, to &s;tand like a puppet, with your leg out, and turn and twi&s;t, ju&s;t as the mini&s;ter pulls the wire fa&s;tened to your jaws, you &s;tupid blocked!</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<PB N="62" REF="56">
<SPEAKER>LD. COL.</SPEAKER>
<P>How!&mdash;this confirms all I have heard &mdash;but I coud'nt have believ'd his in&s;olence ro&s;e to &s;uch a height of&mdash;lay hold of the ungrateful vil|lain!</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>M'GIL.</SPEAKER>
<P>Why my Laird, did you hear me?&mdash;Charley!&mdash;</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>LD. COL.</SPEAKER>
<P>Apprehend him! <STAGE>(Servant &s;eizes him)</STAGE> I wi&s;h, like the ancient Barons, I had the power to hang you on the in&s;tant.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>M'GIL.</SPEAKER>
<P>Oh, my Laird!&mdash;Oh, you rogue Charley!</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>LD. COL.</SPEAKER>
<P>On my authority take him to pri&s;on! 'till he renders an account of his charge&mdash;away with him!</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>M'GIL.</SPEAKER>
<P>Oh, that rogue, Charley!</P>
</SP>
<STAGE>Exeunt Charley into the pre&s;s.</STAGE>
<STAGE>Scene <HI>Shelty's</HI> Hou&s;e.</STAGE>
<STAGE><HI>Enter</HI> Captain Da&s;h <HI>and</HI> Serjeant Jack.</STAGE>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>CAP.</SPEAKER>
<P>Ha, ha, ha!&mdash;well Jack, our &s;ucce&s;s is even beyond my expectation&mdash;I think I &s;hall flap my colours, and you &s;port your halbert in Calcutta: but as &s;oon as we've our compliment of men, we mu&s;t decamp.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>SERJ.</SPEAKER>
<P>I've done my be&s;t, becau&s;e I undertook the thing; but under a fal&s;e hope, trepanning the poor fellows from their homes and families. Pre&s;&s;ing in the &s;ea &s;ervice is a di&s;grace to the Briti&s;h freedom, and a cruel contradiction to Briti&s;h humanity!&mdash;but we are wor&s;e&mdash;we have made the Highlander's loyal affection to his Chief the in&s;trument of his &s;lavery!</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>CAP.</SPEAKER>
<P>Ha, ha, ha&mdash;why Jack, you had none of the&s;e fine morals when I found you a drumm'd out trooper; and on my promi&s;e of an halbert, had your con&s;ent to join in any &s;cheme that might better your fortune.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>SERJ.</SPEAKER>
<P>Why I was drumm'd out, though &s;av'd from la&s;hes by the clemency of my Royal Ma&s;ter; but my only crime was in&s;olence to my officer; I
<PB N="63" REF="57">was &s;aucy, and I de&s;erv'd puni&s;hment&mdash;yet, when a &s;oldier, I never forget I was a man; and now blu&s;h to think, by an act of di&s;honour, I have &s;unk beneath the noble character of an Engli&s;hman!</P>
</SP>
<Q><TEXT LANG="eng">
<BODY>
<DIV1 TYPE="song">
<HEAD>AIR.</HEAD>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Serjeant.</SPEAKER>
<LG>
<L><HI>Old England, great in arts and arms,</HI></L>
<L><HI>For manly worth, and female charms,</HI></L>
<L><HI>Renown'd has ever been;</HI></L>
<L><HI>And now the care of bounteous Heav'n,</HI></L>
<L><HI>Has to happy Allown given</HI></L>
<L><HI>A gracious King and Queen;</HI></L>
<L><HI>In their Royal progeny our blooming pro&s;pects &s;mile,</HI></L>
<L><HI>The fair po&s;&s;e&s;s'd of every grace,</HI></L>
<L><HI>And in the gen'rous &s;ons we trace,</HI></L>
<L><HI>The guardians of our I&s;le.</HI></L>
</LG>
<LG>
<L><HI>On Cra&s;&s;y's plain an Edward fought,</HI></L>
<L><HI>A captive King to London brought,</HI></L>
<L><HI>'Twas there his glories &s;hone;</HI></L>
<L><HI>Tho' terrible in battle, he</HI></L>
<L><HI>Cou'd &s;hew, by God-like clemency,</HI></L>
<L><HI>He grac'd the wreath he won.</HI></L>
<L><HI>Where'er ambition tempts the war, we're ready for the field,</HI></L>
<L><HI>To find a Cre&s;&s;y &s;till in France,</HI></L>
<L><HI>A Royal Fred rick weilds the lance,</HI></L>
<L><HI>And holds Britauma's &s;hield.</HI></L>
</LG>
<LG>
<L><HI>Let fame record Eliza's days,</HI></L>
<L><HI>Her trumpet tune to &s;ongs of prai&s;e,</HI></L>
<L><HI>The grand Armada &s;ee,</HI></L>
<L><HI>The Invincible &s;he overcame,</HI></L>
<L><HI>Spani&s;h pride was turn'd to &s;hame,</HI></L>
<L><HI>By Britons great and free.</HI></L>
<L><HI>Old Neptune thus exulting, to Royal William &s;poke:</HI></L>
<L><HI>If woman once cou'd guard my realm,</HI></L>
<L><HI>What triumph now, when at the helm,</HI></L>
<L><HI>I place a heart of oak,</HI></L>
<L><HI>A Royal heart of oak.</HI></L>
</LG>
</SP>
</DIV1>
</BODY>
</TEXT></Q>
<SP>
<PB N="64" REF="58">
<SPEAKER>CAP.</SPEAKER>
<P>Well, and you &s;hall command men; this Sandy that I've ju&s;t now li&s;ted, is very much of a gentleman&mdash;old M'Gilpin &s;hoving him out of his farm, has ju&s;t plump'd him into our net.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>SERJ.</SPEAKER>
<P>I wou'd certainly fi&s;h up men by hook or by crook; but can't enjoy the pro&s;perity that's built on the de&s;truction of another!</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>CAP.</SPEAKER>
<P>P&s;haw! damn your non&s;en&s;e!&mdash;what the Devil is come to you? this Sandy is&mdash;oh, have you &s;een his Jenny?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>CERJ.</SPEAKER>
<P>Yes, I have &s;een her, and wi&s;h &s;he <HI>was</HI> his.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>CAP.</SPEAKER>
<P>Wi&s;h &s;he was <HI>his</HI> very civil, when you know I love her to di&s;traction&mdash;hey! what's here?</P>
</SP>
<STAGE><HI>Enter</HI> Moggy <HI>from top, dre&s;&s;ed as a Highlander.</HI></STAGE>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>MOG.</SPEAKER>
<P>I beg your honour's pardon, but hasn't your honor li&s;ted one Sandy Frazer?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>CAP.</SPEAKER>
<P>Yes, my lad, and I'll li&s;t you too.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>CERJ.</SPEAKER>
<P>Yes, we'll li&s;t you, if you're willing.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>MOG.</SPEAKER>
<P>It's for that I'm come, if you'll take me in my brother Sandy's place.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>SERJ.</SPEAKER>
<P>Why is Sandy your brother?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>MOG.</SPEAKER>
<P>Yes, Sir, he is, and the elde&s;t of eight little brothers and &s;i&s;ters, not one of them but me, able to earn a mor&s;el of bread for them&s;elves; Sandy and I did tolerably well for them, while he had the farm, as he was able to take care of them, becau&s;e he cou'd manage and provide, and knows ten times more about land not I, from his having been in England&mdash;No, I can never do it; if you take him away, what will become of my brothers and &s;i&s;ters?&mdash;Yes, they'll be &s;tarv'd&mdash;oh, merciful good Captain! take me, and di&s;charge brother Sandy!&mdash;oh!</P>
<STAGE>(cries.)</STAGE>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>CAP.</SPEAKER>
<P>Ha, ha, ha! you young dog, do you bink I'll exchange an effective man for &s;uch a little whipper-&s;napper as you?&mdash;get along, you little monkey!</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>MOG.</SPEAKER>
<P>I am a little monkey!&mdash;oh! I &s;hall never be able to maintain the family!&mdash;oh!</P>
<STAGE>(cries.)</STAGE>
</SP>
<SP>
<PB N="65" REF="59">
<SPEAKER>CAP.</SPEAKER>
<P>Why, Jack, <HI>(to Serj.)</HI> ha, ha, ha! here is another opportunity for your &s;entiments! ha, ha, ha!</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>CERJ.</SPEAKER>
<P>Yes, and for your humanity, if you have any.</P>
<STAGE>(Walks up.)</STAGE>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>CAP.</SPEAKER>
<P>Humanity!&mdash;Eh!&mdash;go home, my boy,</P>
<STAGE>(to Moggy.)</STAGE>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>MOG.</SPEAKER>
<P>Sir, I have rais'd a little bit of money here by &s;elling &s;ome of our &s;tock; if this could make up for my deficiency, till I grow bigger?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>SERJ. </SPEAKER>
<STAGE>(Advancing)</STAGE>
<P>Hey! money!</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>CAP.</SPEAKER>
<P>Money!</P>
<STAGE>Draws her to him.</STAGE>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>MOG.</SPEAKER>
<P>Yes, Sir, if you'll accept this forty pounds and me in the place of my brother Sandy&mdash;Oh, wor|thy noble gentleman! you'll &s;ee what a good fine &s;ol|dier I'll make in time.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>CAP.</SPEAKER>
<P>Eh&mdash;in time&mdash; <STAGE>(looks at her.)</STAGE> Forty pounds&mdash;</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>SERJ.</SPEAKER>
<P>And this yonker will grow taller.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>MOG.</SPEAKER>
<P>Oh, yes, Sir, I intend to grow a deal taller.</P>
</SP>
<Q><TEXT LANG="eng">
<BODY>
<DIV1 TYPE="song">
<HEAD>AIR.</HEAD>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Moggy.</SPEAKER>
<LG>
<L><HI>Tho' I'ma very little lad,</HI></L>
<L><HI>If fighting men cannot be had,</HI></L>
<L><HI>For want of better I may do,</HI></L>
<L><HI>To follow the boy with rat tat too;</HI></L>
<L><HI>I may &s;eem tender, yet I'm tough,</HI></L>
<L><HI>And tho' not much o'me, right good &s;tuff,</HI></L>
<L><HI>Of this I'll boa&s;t, &s;ay more who can,</HI></L>
<L><HI>I never was afraid to meet my man.</HI></L>
<L><HI>I'm a thickabiddy, &s;ee take me now now now,</HI></L>
<L><HI>I'm a little merry he, for your row dow <GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="pdcc" EXTENT="1 word">,</HI></L>
<L><HI>Brown Be&s;s I'll knock about, oh, there's my joy,</HI></L>
<L><HI>At my back a knap&s;ack like a roving boy.</HI></L>
</LG>
<LG>
<L><HI>In my Tartan plaid a young &s;older view.</HI></L>
<L><HI>My phillibeg and dirk, and my bounet blue,</HI></L>
<L><HI>Give the word, and I'll march where you command,</HI></L>
<L><HI>Noble Serjcant, with a &s;hilling &s;trike my hand.</HI></L>
<L><HI>My Captain, as be takes his gla&s;s,</HI></L>
<L><HI>May wi&s;h to toy with a pretty la&s;s,</HI></L>
<L><PB N="66" REF="60"><HI>For &s;uch a one I've a rogui&s;h eye,</HI></L>
<L><HI>He'll never want a girl when I am by.</HI></L>
<L><HI>I'm a chickabiddy, &amp;c,</HI></L>
<L><HI>Tho' a barber never yet has mow'd my chin,</HI></L>
<L><HI>With my great broad &s;word I long to begin,</HI></L>
<L><HI>Cut, &s;la&s;h, ram damn&mdash;oh glorious fun,</HI></L>
<L><HI>For a gun, pip, pop, change my little pop-gun.</HI></L>
<L><HI>My foes &s;hall fly like gee&s;e in flocks,</HI></L>
<L><HI>Ev'n Turks I'll drive like turkey-cocks,</HI></L>
<L><HI>And where ever quarter'd I &s;hall be,</HI></L>
<L><HI>Oh, Zounds! how I'll ki&s;s my landlady,</HI></L>
<L><HI>I'm a chickabiddy, &amp;c</HI></L>
</LG>
</SP>
</DIV1>
</BODY>
</TEXT></Q>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>CAP.</SPEAKER>
<P>Ha, ha, ha!&mdash;well, my little-tall boy&mdash; <STAGE>(He writes in his pocket-book, and tears a leaf out, which he gives to Moggy.)</STAGE> Ha, ha, ha!&mdash;there's your brother Sandy's di&s;charge&mdash;I take your forty pounds&mdash;there, a &s;hilling.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>MOG.</SPEAKER>
<P>A &s;hilling!&mdash;generous Captain! thank'ye, Sir&mdash;this paper&mdash;what a pre&s;ent for my poor Jenny!</P>
<STAGE>(a&s;ide, with joy)</STAGE>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>SERJ.</SPEAKER>
<P>Sir, we are lucky rogues! this forty pounds comes to us mo&s;t <HI>apropos!</HI></P>
<STAGE>(apart to Captain)</STAGE>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>CAP.</SPEAKER>
<P><HI>Us!</HI>&mdash;what do you mean, fellow?&mdash;In profit I am <HI>&s;olus.</HI> <STAGE>(To Moggy,)</STAGE> now you are the King's man.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>SERJ.</SPEAKER>
<P>And Sandy is his own.</P>
</SP>
<STAGE><HI>Enter</HI> Sandy <HI>(as a Recruit) and</HI> Shelty.</STAGE>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>MOG. </SPEAKER>
<STAGE>(Giving Sandy the paper &s;he received from the Captain.)</STAGE>
<P>There's your di&s;charge, Sandy; no more the King's, you're now only Jenny's man.</P>
</SP>
<STAGE><HI>Enter</HI> Jenny.</STAGE>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>CEN.</SPEAKER>
<P>Ah, Sandy! how cou'd you for&s;ake me?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>CAP.</SPEAKER>
<P>Hey! the Devil!&mdash;what's all this about? &mdash;here, you little bu&s;y ra&s;cal, <STAGE>(to Moggy.)</STAGE> True, my lad, <STAGE>(to Sandy)</STAGE> as he &s;ays, you're free, but I'll or|der your pert young brother here up the halberts&mdash;</P>
</SP>
<STAGE>(points to Moggy.)</STAGE>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>SAN.</SPEAKER>
<P>My&mdash;I've no brother!</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>CAP.</SPEAKER>
<P>Eh!&mdash;why, what the devil is all this you've been telling me, firrah?</P>
<STAGE>(to Moggy.)</STAGE>
</SP>
<SP>
<PB N="67" REF="61">
<SPEAKER>MOC.</SPEAKER>
<P>Oh, Lord! Sir, I'm the greate&s;t fibber you ever knew.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>CAP.</SPEAKER>
<P>Why, damme, you little &s;on of a gun&mdash;</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>MOG.</SPEAKER>
<P>No, Sir, but I happen to be <HI>daughter</HI> to an old great gun!</P>
</SP>
<STAGE><HI>Enter</HI> Charley.</STAGE>
<P>Here's my match, <STAGE><HI>(takes his hand)</HI>&mdash;</STAGE> and hey! I'm off like a &s;ky-rocket. <STAGE>(Runs off with Charley.)</STAGE></P>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>JEN.</SPEAKER>
<P>Sandy, didn't you know her?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>SAN.</SPEAKER>
<P>But, my dear, what has &s;he been about here?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>JEN.</SPEAKER>
<P>Oh, Sandy, &s;he's a worthy girl.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>CAP.</SPEAKER>
<P>She!&mdash;a woman!&mdash;Oh, zounds! have I parted with an Alexander, to make a &s;oldier of&mdash;</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>SHEL.</SPEAKER>
<P>A &s;oldier!&mdash;ha, ha, ha!&mdash;the Captain has been li&s;ting Moggy M'Gilpin, ha, ha, ha!</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>SAN.</SPEAKER>
<P>Ha, ha, ha!</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>JEN.</SPEAKER>
<P>My dear whim&s;ical good-natured friend!&mdash;may &s;he be as happy with the lad of her heart as &s;he has made me with my Sandy!</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>CAP.</SPEAKER>
<P>Oh, ho&mdash;I &s;ee it now&mdash;you have been a con|federate in this impo&s;ition,</P>
<STAGE>(to Sandy.)</STAGE>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>SAN.</SPEAKER>
<P>Totally innocent; and yet <HI>Captain,</HI> I'm an impo&s;tor, as well as your&s;elf.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>CAP.</SPEAKER>
<P>How?</P>
<STAGE>(angry.)</STAGE>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>LD. COL. </SPEAKER>
<STAGE>(Without.)</STAGE>
<P>This way&mdash;come, come.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>CAP.</SPEAKER>
<P>Damme, I'll&mdash;</P>
<STAGE>(Threatening Sandy.)</STAGE>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>SAN.</SPEAKER>
<P>Nay, Sir, no bouncing&mdash;for here comes an old gentleman that will find us both out.</P>
</SP>
<STAGE><HI>Enter</HI> Laird <HI>of</HI> Col, <HI>and</HI> M'Gilpin.</STAGE>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>LD. COL. </SPEAKER>
<STAGE>(To M'Gilpin)</STAGE>
<P>Sir, you &s;tand upon your own guilt or innocene&mdash;you've turn'd the &s;word of ju&s;tice into a raping-hook, and her balance to a money &s;cale&mdash;but it's putting a weapon into the hands of a madman, to give power, where the mind is ba&s;e and venal; &s;o expect no favour from me.&mdash;And pray, Sir, <STAGE>(to Cap.)</STAGE> by who&s;e authority do you li&s;t men in this i&s;land?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>CAP.</SPEAKER>
<P>Our King, and my Colonel.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>LD. Col.</SPEAKER>
<P>Who is your Colonel?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>CAP.</SPEAKER>
<P>The owner of this i&s;land, my friend, young Bob M'Donald.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<PB N="68" REF="62">
<SPEAKER>LD. COL.</SPEAKER>
<P>Well, this is rather odd; my &s;on a Colonel! the fir&s;t time I ever heard he was even in the army!</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>CAP.</SPEAKER>
<P>Son!&mdash;Jack, <STAGE>(to Serj.)</STAGE> Zounds, if&mdash;can this be the old Lai d?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>LD. COL. </SPEAKER>
<STAGE>(Seeing Sandy)</STAGE>
<P>Eh! is't po&s;&s;ible? Bob!</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>CAP.</SPEAKER>
<P>Why, Sir, do you know this Sandy?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>LD. COL.</SPEAKER>
<P>What do you mean by Sandy? This is my &s;on Robert, ha, ha, ha!&mdash;your friend&mdash;young Bob M'Donald.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>M'GIL.</SPEAKER>
<P>What, Sandy our young Laird!</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>LD. COL.</SPEAKER>
<P>Ha, ha, ha!&mdash;But Bob, if you are a colo|nel, as this Gentleman &s;ays, I don't admire the mode of your regimentals.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>SAN.</SPEAKER>
<P>Why, no, Sir&mdash;but this gentleman dubs him&s;elf a Captain, his friend Bob a Colonel, and then cruelly degrades me to a private in my own re|giment, ha, ha, ha!</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>CAP.</SPEAKER>
<P>This young Donald? confu&s;ion!&mdash;Jack, we are undone&mdash;yes, they'll hang us,</P>
<STAGE>(apart.)</STAGE>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>SERJ. </SPEAKER>
<STAGE>(Aloud)</STAGE>
<P><HI>Us!</HI>&mdash;what do you mean, follow? In hanging you are <HI>&s;olus</HI>&mdash;</P>
<STAGE>(mimicks the Captains former manner.)</STAGE>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>SHEL.</SPEAKER>
<P>Yes, the Captain goes up.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>LD. COL.</SPEAKER>
<P>Oh, I conceive now&mdash;then Bob, you are the Sandy I've heard &s;o much of for improving the land; but why di&s;grace you&s;elf and family, by turn|plough-boy your&s;elf, lad?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>SAN.</SPEAKER>
<P>Sir, nothing di&s;graces any family but a di&s;|honourable action; and of that I am uncon&s;cious. I came hither, as I told you I &s;hould on my &s;hooting &s;cheme; but on the in&s;tant of my arrival, a tran&s;ient &s;ight of this lady in&s;pir'd me with the de&s;ign, which has made me the happie&s;t of men. In this &s;eque&s;ter'd I &s;le I have found this lovely flower, who&s;e difintere&s;t|ed &s;miles upon the farmer, have proved &s;he mu&s;t grace the bo&s;om of the Laird.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>LD. COL.</SPEAKER>
<P>But, Bob, &s;till your whole conduct (to me wears a face of my&s;tery, your turning common &s;oldier&mdash;how?&mdash;Come, Sir, I in&s;i&s;t upon a full and clear explanation.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<PB N="69" REF="63">
<SPEAKER>SAN.</SPEAKER>
<P>Sir, my motives for enli&s;ting were, to &s;ecure this gentleman's conviction, for his very impudent fraud, founded on a forgery of my name&mdash;and by fabricating <HI>imaginary</HI> di&s;tre&s;&s;es, have prov'd how far true love wou'd go to alleviate a real one.</P>
</SP>
<STAGE><HI>Enter</HI> Laird <HI>of</HI> Rau&s;ey.</STAGE>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>LD. R.</SPEAKER>
<P>Well, I am come to bid you, farewel, Donald.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>LD. COL.</SPEAKER>
<P>Going?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>LD. R.</SPEAKER>
<P>Yes, when I &s;ettle&mdash;but where is this lad? I don't know how to find this Sandy Frazer out.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>LD. COL!</SPEAKER>
<P>Ha, ha, ha!&mdash;Oh, Sir, there &s;tands the gentleman,</P>
<STAGE>points to Sandy.</STAGE>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>LD. R.</SPEAKER>
<P>An hone&s;t looking youth&mdash;young man, you'll marry Jenny?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>SAN.</SPEAKER>
<P>If &s;he will honour me.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>LD. R.</SPEAKER>
<P>It is an honour, if you knew all. <STAGE>(A&s;ide.)</STAGE> Here's an hundred pounds with her; don't a&s;k why I give you this&mdash;&s;he's wild and vulgar, but keep a tight rein, and you may reclaim her.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>SAN.</SPEAKER>
<P>Sir, who&s;oever you are keep your advice and money for tho&s;e who want them.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>SHEL.</SPEAKER>
<P>Want them! then, Sir, give my father the advice, and me the money.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>JEN.</SPEAKER>
<P>Sir, <STAGE>(to Ld. of R.)</STAGE> tho' I have not the honour of knowing you, and wou'd wi&s;h not to de&s;erve the character you are pleas'd to give me, yet I humbly thank you for your generous intention.</P>
<STAGE>(Curt&s;ies with much grace and mode&s;ty.)</STAGE>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>LD. R.</SPEAKER>
<P>You, madam!&mdash;I mean Jenny!</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>SAN.</SPEAKER>
<P>Well, Sir, this is &s;he!</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>LD. R.</SPEAKER>
<P>This!&mdash;why, you are not the young wo|man was wanting me to marry you ju&s;t now?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>JEN.</SPEAKER>
<P>Me, Sir,&mdash;to my recollection, I never &s;aw you before.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>SHEL.</SPEAKER>
<P>The Doctor has been taking his whi&s;key.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>LD. R.</SPEAKER>
<P>Very odd this; I mu&s;t have been impos'd on.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>SHFL.</SPEAKER>
<P>Oh, yes, they forget to mix it for you.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>LD. R.</SPEAKER>
<P>Pray, Madam, who are your parents?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>JEN.</SPEAKER>
<P>I know not.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>LD. R. </SPEAKER>
<STAGE>(Seeing M'Gil.)</STAGE>
<P>Oh, Sir, from you I ex|pect, and mu&s;t exact, a con&s;irmation of what indeed
<PB N="70" REF="64">I &s;carce entertain a doubt, <STAGE>(looking at Jenny.)</STAGE> Tell me what you know of this young woman.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>M'GIL.</SPEAKER>
<P>Fir&s;t, Sir, tell me am I obliged to tell you?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>LD. COL.</SPEAKER>
<P>You are, <HI>authoritatively.</HI></P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>M'GIL.</SPEAKER>
<P>Then, Sir, you mu&s;t know&mdash;upon my word, my memory is &s;o very bad, I can't recollect any thing at all of the matter.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>LD. R.</SPEAKER>
<P>What, Sir, not recollect the 500l. left her by her <HI>mother?</HI></P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>M'GIL.</SPEAKER>
<P>The <HI>five</HI> pounds! Zounds, I tell you, if I was even on a trial, I never could remember what I was determined to forget&mdash;however, Sir, if as I now find, you are the Laird of Rau&s;ey, I'll make a free confe&s;&s;ion, if 'twill do me any good.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>LD. R.</SPEAKER>
<P>Well, Sir&mdash;</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>M'GIL.</SPEAKER>
<P>This is your very neice, the &s;weet babe that was born in my hou&s;e.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>LD. R.</SPEAKER>
<P>'Tis confirm'd&mdash;I &s;aw there the features of my beloved unhappy &s;i&s;ter, <STAGE>(to Ld. of Col.)</STAGE> I now, with pride acknowledge her for my neice.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>LD. COL.</SPEAKER>
<P>Do you?&mdash;Oh, then I acknowledge her formy daughter-in-law.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>SHEL.</SPEAKER>
<P>Hard now that I can't turn out to be &s;ome body el&s;e.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>M'GIL. </SPEAKER>
<STAGE>(To Sandy)</STAGE>
<P>I prote&s;t, Sir, had I known you were the Laird, I'd never have turn'd you out of your farm.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>SAN.</SPEAKER>
<P>Ha, ha, ha!&mdash;Why, I believe you.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>M'GIL.</SPEAKER>
<P>So, Sir, I hope you'll procure my Laird's pardon for the genteel manner in which I ha Mi&s;s Jenny brought up at Mi&s;s Kilcooburry's boarding|&s;chool, at Inverne&s;s&mdash;you know, Mi&s;s, what a fu&s;s I made about you when a little fat pup et.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>JEN.</SPEAKER>
<P>Indeed, Sir, whatever may have been his other failings, to me he has prov'd an affectionate guardian&mdash;permit me, Sir, to recommend to your fa|vour the worthy &s;erjeant here, to who&s;e unexpected genero&s;ity I partly owe my pre&s;ent happine&s;s.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>JACK.</SPEAKER>
<P>Thank'yee, Ma'am&mdash;I own I came here on a very rogui&s;h plan, which, if you can prevail on the young Laird to pardon, <STAGE>(looks at Sandy)</STAGE> let it
<PB N="71" REF="65">extend to my friend, the Captain&mdash;'twas I that led him here, to help my recruiting &s;cheme&mdash;we were partners in the guilt.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>SAN.</SPEAKER>
<P>Recruiting, call you it&mdash;kidnapping&mdash;a di&s;|grace to your profe&s;&s;ion&mdash;for in your zeal for the &s;er|vice, remember, that honour is the characteri&s;tic of an Engli&s;h officer.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>M'GIL.</SPEAKER>
<P>But now your ju&s;tice, my Laird, on this curs'd, juggling, conjuring piper, who has, without my con&s;ent, run away with, and married my daughter.</P>
</SP>
<STAGE><HI>Enter</HI> Charley, <HI>leading</HI> Moggy <HI>in a Highland dre&s;s.</HI></STAGE>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>CHAR. </SPEAKER>
<STAGE>(To M'Gil.)</STAGE>
<P>Sir, give me leave to introduce Captain M'Gilpin.</P>
<STAGE>(pre&s;enting Moggy.)</STAGE>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>M'GIL.</SPEAKER>
<P>Moggy!&mdash;Oh!&mdash;you brazen face!&mdash;hey &mdash;turn'd &s;oldier?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>MOG.</SPEAKER>
<P>I am, Sir, and under the command of General Charley&mdash;the real par&s;on, who is now below at the door, gave the word&mdash;'twas love, honour, and obey.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>LD. R. </SPEAKER>
<STAGE>(Looking at Mog.)</STAGE>
<P>Ay, ay, this is the young lady that is &s;o clever at fibbing&mdash;how do you do, Mi&s;s Jenny?</P>
<STAGE>(plea&s;ant.)</STAGE>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>MOG.</SPEAKER>
<P>Pretty well, I thank you, ma&s;ter <HI>Par&s;on!</HI></P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>LD. COL.</SPEAKER>
<P>My dear &s;on, the noble manner in which you have made your choice, with all my family pride, gives me infinite plea&s;ure&mdash;Madam, I wi&s;h you joy. <STAGE>(to Jenny)</STAGE> Your affections have been prov'd, and you mu&s;t both be happy&mdash;where viriue and innocence re|&s;ide Heaven is the orphan's friend; and I wi&s;h every fond pair, who marry for love, may thus be agrec|ably &s;urpris'd with money.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>SHEL.</SPEAKER>
<P>If I was &s;ure of that, I'd marry for love my|&s;elf; &s;o I'm a conjuror!&mdash;the&s;e are comical conjura|tions &mdash;the tenant is the landlord&mdash;the poor orphan is the Lady of the land&mdash;the Captain is no &s;oldier&mdash;the &s;oldier is a woman&mdash;the apprentice is the ma&s;ter&mdash;the ma&s;ter is&mdash;no body&mdash;the poor par&s;on is a Laird of much land. <STAGE>(Looking at them by turns.)</STAGE>&mdash;and poor Shel|ty, the Scotch piper&mdash;Oh, your humbe &s;ervant to command. <STAGE>(Bows to them)</STAGE>&mdash;and whether I tap the barrel, or tune the chaunter&mdash;Hey! neighbours, let's all be merry&mdash;</P>
</SP>
<DIV3 TYPE="finale">
<PB N="72" REF="66">
<HEAD>FINALE.</HEAD>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>San.</SPEAKER>
<L><HI>Come &s;prightly Lowland la&s;s,</HI></L>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Shel.</SPEAKER>
<L><HI>And Highland lad, trip here in jovial glee,</HI></L>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>San.</SPEAKER>
<L><HI>Gentle winds from ev'ry i&s;land,</HI></L>
<L><HI>Waft hearts merry, blyth and free;</HI></L>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Shel.</SPEAKER>
<L><HI>At Shelty's hou&s;e in gay carou&s;e your hours employ,</HI></L>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>M'Gil.</SPEAKER>
<L><HI>O well &s;aid boy;</HI></L>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Serj.</SPEAKER>
<L><HI>Lay &s;upper down, and bring the booze,</HI></L>
<L><HI>To wi&s;h the young folks love and joy.</HI></L>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Chorus.</SPEAKER>
<L><HI>Whi&s;key, fri&s;ky, prancing, dancing,</HI></L>
<L><HI>Sorrow &s;end to Nick the De'el,</HI></L>
<L><HI>Care or trouble, who can feel,</HI></L>
<L><HI>Lifting up the Highland Reel.</HI></L>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>MOG.</SPEAKER>
<L><HI>Mind, deare&s;t lad, I tell you fairly,</HI></L>
<L><HI>Married I mu&s;t have my way,</HI></L>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Char.</SPEAKER>
<L><HI>I'm &s;ure, dear la&s;s, you'll gowern rarcly,</HI></L>
<L><HI>Love and honour I'll obey;</HI></L>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>San.</SPEAKER>
<L><HI>Nor marriage chain,</HI></L>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Shel.</SPEAKER>
<L><HI>Nor bit nor rein;</HI></L>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Mog.</SPEAKER>
<L><HI>The Duce a bit,</HI></L>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>M'Gil.</SPEAKER>
<L><HI>A game&s;ome tit,</HI></L>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Shel.</SPEAKER>
<L><HI>Gadzooks poor henpeck'd Charley,</HI></L>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>M'Gil.</SPEAKER>
<L><HI>A wi&s;e man I, my child's a wit.&mdash;Whi&s;key, &amp;c.</HI></L>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>San.</SPEAKER>
<L><HI>The torch of love by Cupid lighted,</HI></L>
<L><HI>Never &s;hall extingui&s;h'd lie.</HI></L>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Jen.</SPEAKER>
<L><HI>True vows at Hymen's altar plighted.</HI></L>
<L><HI>Ro&s;y hours the knot &s;hall tie;</HI></L>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>San.</SPEAKER>
<L><HI>Earne&s;t this,</HI></L>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Jen.</SPEAKER>
<L><HI>Of Heavenly bli&s;s,</HI></L>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Both.</SPEAKER>
<L><HI>My only love,</HI></L>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>M'Gil.</SPEAKER>
<L><HI>Well &s;aid, by Jove;</HI></L>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>San.</SPEAKER>
<L><HI>Sweet blo&s;&s;om ne'er be blighted,</HI></L>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>M'Gil.</SPEAKER>
<L><HI>She'll cooe like any turtle dove.&mdash;Whi&s;key, &amp;c.</HI></L>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Serj.</SPEAKER>
<L><HI>Old Neptune's arms the globe embracing,</HI></L>
<L><HI>In his gra&s;p can kingdoms hem,</HI></L>
<L><HI>Great Jove upon his fingers placing,</HI></L>
<L><HI>Albion's I&s;le, a radient gem;</HI></L>
<L><HI>Oh, ever &s;hine with rays divine,</HI></L>
<L><HI>Shed lu&s;tre round, and thus enthron'd,</HI></L>
<L><HI>Roval George with years encrea&s;ing,</HI></L>
<L><HI>With each ble&s;&s;ing ever crown'd.&mdash;Whi&s;key, &amp;c.</HI></L>
</SP>
</DIV3>
</DIV2>
<TRAILER>FINIS.</TRAILER>
